# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-ii-of-russia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The **2011–2013 Russian protests**, which some English language media referred to as the **Snow Revolution** (Russian: Снежная революция, romanised: *Snezhnaya revolyutsiya*), began in 2011 (as protests against the 2011 Russian legislative election results) and continued into 2012 and 2013.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The protests were motivated by claims of Russian and foreign journalists, political activists and members of the public that the election process was fraudulent.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Central Election Commission of Russia stated that 195 out of 1,686 official reports of fraud (11.5%) could be confirmed as true.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 10 December 2011, after a week of small-scale demonstrations, Russia saw some of the biggest protests in Moscow since the 1990s.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The focus of the protests were the ruling party, United Russia, and its leader Vladimir Putin, the prime minister and former president, who announced his intention to run for president again in 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Another round of large protests took place on 24 December 2011.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] These protests were named "For Fair Elections" (Russian: За честные выборы) and their organisers set up the movement of the same name.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Initial protest actions, organised by the leaders of the Russian opposition parties and non-systemic opposition sparked fear in some quarters of a colour revolution in Russia, and a number of counter-protests and rallies in support of the government were held.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On the first days following the election, Putin and United Russia were supported by rallies of two youth organisations, the government-organised Nashi and United Russia's Young Guard.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 24 December Sergey Kurginyan organised the first protest against what was viewed as "orange" protesters in Moscow, though the protest also went under the same slogan "For Fair Elections".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 4 February 2012, more protests and pro-government rallies were held throughout the country.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 6 May 2012, protests took place in Moscow the day before Putin's inauguration as President for his third term.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some called for the inauguration to be scrapped.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The protests were marred by violence between the protesters and the police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] About 400 protesters were arrested, including Alexei Navalny, Boris Nemtsov and Sergei Udaltsov and 80 were injured.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On the day of the inauguration, 7 May, at least 120 protesters were arrested in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In June 2012, laws were enacted which set strict boundaries on protests and imposed heavy penalties for unauthorised actions.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] As of January 2013, interviews by Ellen Barry of *The New York Times* of working class elements which had supported the protests revealed an atmosphere of intimidation, discouragement, and alienation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In the 2000s, due to increased restrictions in the election legislation and the takeover of large media under state control, a non-system opposition emerged, which was barred from participation in elections.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] This time, it included both left and right organisations as well as nationalists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The largest protests and main opposition events include rallies to support the old NTV staff (2001), mass protests against Mikhail Zurabov's reforms (2005), Dissenters' March (2005–2008), Russian Marches, "I am free!
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to RIA Novosti, there were more than 1,100 official reports of election irregularities across the country, including allegations of vote fraud, obstruction of observers and illegal campaigning.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Members of the A Just Russia, Yabloko and Communist parties reported that voters were shuttled between multiple polling stations to cast several ballots.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Yabloko and LDPR parties reported that some of their observers had been banned from witnessing the sealing of the ballot boxes and from gathering video footage, and some were groundlessly expelled from polling stations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The ruling United Russia party alleged that the opposition parties had engaged in illegal campaigning by distributing leaflets and newspapers at polling stations and that at some polling stations the voters had been ordered to vote for the Communist party with threats of violence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] There were several reports of almost undetectable vote fraud—swapping of final polling station protocols just before final accounting by station chairmen—that happened late at night when most observers were gone.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Central Electoral Commission issued a report on 3 February 2012, in which it said that it received the total of 1686 reports on irregularities, of which only 195 (11.5%) were upheld after investigation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A third (584) actually contained questions about the unclear points of electoral law, and only 60 complaints were claiming falsifications of the elections results.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Despite the official findings, protests carried on up to and beyond 4 March presidential election.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to *The New York Times*, the leading element has consisted of young urban professionals, the well-educated and successful working or middle-class people such as workers in social media.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] These groups had benefited from substantial growth in the Russian economy until the 2008 economic crisis but have been alienated by increasing political corruption as well as recent stagnation in their income.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The number of such individuals is large and growing in urban centres and is thought to represent a challenge to continuation of authoritarian rule.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to Putin the legitimate grievances of this young and active element of Russian society are being exploited by opportunistic elements which seek to destabilise Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Nationalist elements play a significant role in the coalition which is organising and participating in the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 4 November 2011, during the annual Russian March event, representatives of "The Russians" movement declared a protest action planned for election day after polling districts closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] As there was no official rally permit, the action by "The Russians" was unapproved and took place on 4 December at 21:00 in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The statement of non-recognition of electoral results spread widely. Сitizens were called upon to create self-governing institutions reflecting national interests and were told of falsifications and frauds said to have occurred during the elections.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Alexander Belov declared the beginning of the "Putin, go away!" campaign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The protest action, in which several hundreds persons participated, led to running battles with riot police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Leaders of "The Russians" Alexander Belov, Dmitry Dyomushkin, George Borovikov were arrested along with dozens of other nationalists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The head of the banned Movement Against Illegal Immigration organisation Vladimir Yermolaev was detained at a voting station where he was an observer.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Mass detentions of other public organisations occurred in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to police some 258 persons have been detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 5 December, around 5,000 opponents of the government began protesting in Moscow, denouncing Vladimir Putin and his government and what they believed were flawed elections.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Campaigners argued that the elections had been a sham and demanded that Putin step down, whilst some demanded revolution.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Alexei Navalny, a top blogger and anti-corruption activist who branded Putin's United Russia party as the "party of crooks and thieves", is credited with initial mobilisation of mass protests through postings on his LiveJournal blog and Twitter account.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Navalny's agitation was denounced by United Russia as "typical dirty self-promotion" and a profane tweet describing Navalny as a sheep engaged in oral sex originated from Medvedev's Twitter account.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Many pro-government supporters, including the pro-Putin youth group Nashi, were mobilised on 6 December at the site of the planned demonstration where they made noise in support of the government and United Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] There was a 15,000-strong rally of Nashi on Manezhnaya Square and an 8,000-strong rally of the Young Guard on Revolution Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] About 500 pro-United Russia activists marched near Red Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Truckloads of soldiers and police, as well as a water cannon, were deployed ahead of expected anti-government protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] It emerged that 300 protesters had been arrested in Moscow the night before, along with 120 in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] During the night of 6 December, at least 600 protesters were reported to be in Triumphalnaya square chanting slogans against Putin, whilst anti-government protesters at Revolution Square clashed with riot police and interior ministry troops.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The police chased around 100 away, arresting some.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Protest numbers later reportedly reached over 1,000 at Triumphalnaya Square and dozens of arrests were reported, including Boris Nemtsov, an opposition leader and former deputy prime minister, and Alexey Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Over 250 arrests were made, with police using buses to transport the suspects to police stations to be charged.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At least one Russian journalist claimed he was beaten by police officers who stamped on him and hit his legs with batons.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Another 200 arrests were reported in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Petersburg and 25 in Rostov the same night as anti-government demonstrations took place.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After three and a half hours, the Moscow protest came to an end.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Attempts to stage a large protest in Moscow on 7 December fizzled out due to a large police presence in the city.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Via a Facebook group "Суббота на Болотной площади" (Saturday at Bolotnaya Square), a call was made for a mass protest against the government on Saturday 10 December.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Prior to the demonstration newspapers commented that tens of thousands of Facebook users had positively responded to invitations to demonstrate in Moscow, and, similarly, over 5,000 in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A permit had originally been issued to the group Solidarnost for a legal demonstration of 300 people in Revolution Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] By 8 December, more than 30,000 had accepted the Facebook invitation to attend.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After negotiations with the demonstrators an alternative location for a 30,000-person demonstration was authorised by the Moscow government for the demonstration which took place on 10 December on Bolotnaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Prior to the demonstration, threats were made by Putin that police and security forces would be deployed to deal with anyone participating in illegal protests in Moscow or other cities; however, the event, when it took place, was peaceful and without attempts by the state to prevent or disrupt it.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Rapper Noize MC and author Boris Akunin both agreed to address the crowds, the latter flying in specially from Paris for the occasion.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Guerrilla theatre by FEMEN and the circulation of a photoshopped image of Putin dressed as Muammar Gaddafi accompanied the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Attempts to disrupt the protests and the organisations supporting them included repeated prank calls to Yabloko and Novaya Gazeta.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Russia's chief public health official, Gennady Onishchenko, warned on Friday that protesters risked respiratory infections such as the flu or SARS.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Warnings were issued that the police would be looking for draft dodgers at the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Guardian also reported that mobile internet had been "cut off" in the square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Moscow demonstration was generally peaceful ending in the afternoon with the singing of Viktor Tsoi's song "Peremen" meaning "Changes", a perestroika anthem from the 1980s.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Reports of the demonstration including its large size and demands for new elections were carried on the evening news in Russia by state controlled media.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Police in Moscow estimated the protest numbers to be around 25,000, whilst the opposition claimed over 50,000 people were present during the demonstration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Other activists claimed as many as 60,000 protesters in Bolotnaya Square, Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Like in Moscow, protests were planned to take place in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Petersburg, Vladivostok and Kaliningrad, as well as 88 other towns and cities in Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Smaller protests were reported in Tomsk, Omsk, Arkhangelsk, Murmansk, Yekaterinburg, Novosibirsk, Krasnoyarsk, Kurgan, Perm, Karelia, Khabarovsk, Kazan and Nizhny Novgorod.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At least 10,000 protesters turned out in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Petersburg, 3,000 in Novosibirsk, whilst 4,000 others rallied in Yekaterinburg.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At least 1,000 people rallied in the port city of Vladivostok on Russia's Pacific coast.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] "Sympathy protests" are also being held abroad.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In London, the former parliamentary aide accused of being a Russian spy Katia Zatuliveter turned up holding a banner saying: "Russian vote 146 per cent fair".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some sources report only 100 arrests nationwide on 10 December due to the protests, mostly outside Moscow, which is a significantly smaller number than previous protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In Kazan, however, at least 100 protesters, mainly in their early 20s, were detained for failure to disperse.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 17 December another meeting was held at Bolotnaya Square in Moscow against the election fraud.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The rally was organised by Yabloko but members of other political parties participated as well.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Among the speakers were Grigory Yavlinsky and Sergey Mitrokhin from Yabloko and Vladimir Ryzhkov from the People's Freedom Party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Moscow Police claimed there were 1500 demonstrators but eyewitnesses claimed there were up to 5000 people at the peak of the demonstration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In any case, the turnout was far below that of the multi-party rally of 10 December.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A rally was held on 18 December in Moscow, organised by Communist Party of the Russian Federation in Moscow and took place at Manezhnaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Several thousand supporters turned out, but many were elderly.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Another smaller rally took place in Saint Petersburg at Pionerskaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Gennady Zyuganov, head of the party and its candidate for President of Russia, has denounced election regularities but has also expressed his opposition to the organisers of the mass demonstrations who he views as ultra liberals who are exploiting unrest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] There were large follow-up demonstrations 24 December including a rally "For Fair Elections" at Academician Sakharov Avenue in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] There were rallies in Vladivostok, Novosibirsk, Orenburg, Chelyabinsk, Saratov, Nizhny Novgorod and two in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A podium was built at the end of the 700-metre (0.43-mile) avenue.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The atmosphere was peaceful but at least 40 bus loads of riot police were standing by as thousands of protesters demonstrated, with a total of up to 50,000 expected to arrive during the day.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Alexei Kudrin, a former Putin insider, spoke advocating dialogue.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] He was booed by some, but cheered by others.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At least 21,000 protesters were in Moscow by 11:10 am GMT, according to Itar Tass, and there were at least 100 arrests in Vladivostok.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to on scene reporters, the atmosphere was fun, with white ribbons and balloons and condom-themed banners – a mocking reference to Vladimir Putin saying he believed the white ribbons, the protest movements symbol, were to promote safe sex.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The Interior Ministry estimated that at least 28,000 people had turned up, whilst some in the opposition claimed 120,000 protesters were in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Reporters of the *Moscow Times* said the figure was well above the 30,000 to 60,000 at the previous event and that there were about 80,000 protesters who came to this rally.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The infographics from RIA Novosti shows that the Sakharov Avenue can provide room for a maximum of 96,000 people at a density of 35 people per 10 sq m, or for 55,000 people at a smaller and more realistic density distribution.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Alexei Navalny, greeted with a ovation when he finally spoke, said there were enough people present at the protest to march to and overrun the Kremlin, but that they were committed to remaining peaceful, at least for the moment.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The crowd reportedly included liberals, anarchists, communists, nationalists and monarchists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Mikhail Gorbachev did not attend or speak but sent a message of support.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On the day of the rally, the former Soviet president called on Putin to resign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Mikhail Prokhorov, the billionaire independent presidential candidate, was in the crowd but did not speak.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Speakers have been arranged by Alexei Navalny, Garry Kasparov, Boris Nemtsov, and Vladimir Tor, based on the principle of representation of different political forces.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The last speaker was Grandfather Frost who wished everyone a "Happy New Year".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 19 December, Lifenews.ru news portal published a recording of phone conversations ascribed to Boris Nemtsov, the leader of PARNAS People's Freedom Party, and one of the main organisers of the demonstration on Bolotnaya square on 10 December.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In other recordings, he used profanities and referenced to the sexual life of some other leaders of the demonstration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] He also called another prominent leader of protests, Alexei Navalny "a specialist of manipulating the internet mob".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Nemtsov later apologised to several leaders he characterised in these conversations, but not to protesters, and claimed that people that made recordings available to the public committed a crime.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Lifenews.ru claimed at least 3 million visitors coming to the site during the day, and the site was not accessible for some time.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Despite temperatures of −20 degrees Celsius a third demonstration was carried out in Moscow by the For Fair Elections movement on 4 February, with 160,000 participants according to organisers or 38,000 participants according to the police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to the state-run Ria Novosti's calculations, the Bolotnaya Square site provides room for a maximum of 101,000 people at a maximum density of 35 people per 10 sq m on the quay and 15 people per 10 sq m in the park, or for 53,000 people at a smaller and less compact density distribution.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] This time the demonstration started with a march from Kaluzhskaya Square to Bolotnaya Square where a meeting was held.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The anti-Putin protesters carried white balloons and were wearing white ribbons.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Among the speakers were Yevgeniya Chirikova, Gennady Gudkov, Leonid Parfyonov, Olga Romanova, Vladimir Ryzhkov, Sergei Udaltsov, Ilya Yashin and Grigory Yavlinsky.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The meeting was ended by Yuri Shevchuk who sang his famous song "Rodina" (Motherland).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The same day demonstrations were being held in other cities throughout Russia such as St Petersburg, Kazan, Kaliningrad, Nizhni Novgorod, Penza and Yaroslavl.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Also the Russian-speaking population of other countries organised rallies worldwide with similar demands: Germany, Israel, USA.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The organisers of the third Moscow "For Fair Elections" protest had difficulties originally financing the protest because contributions from the public had waned by January 2012, so they financed the organisation of the protest with money collected earlier for other events.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] During February 2012, when residents of the Siberian city of Barnaul were denied a permit for a street protest, they ingeniously circumvented the restriction by staging a demonstration with toys such as teddy bears, Lego figures, and toy soldiers holding signs denouncing electoral corruption.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The photos of these rebellious figurines quickly spread across Russia, prompting others to replicate the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Faced with an awkward dilemma, Putin's government decided to ban the toy protests, asserting that toys, not being Russian citizens, were ineligible to participate in public gatherings, as explained by a government official.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At least 3,500 people demonstrated against Vladimir Putin in St Petersburg, under heavy police presence, but no arrests were made.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In Moscow on Sunday 26 February up to 30,000 people lined the Garden Ring in a protest called the Big White Circle.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] White clothes and white ribbons were worn as protestors formed a nine-mile human chain holding a white banner.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The event was described as an apolitical "act of unity" to avoid the official permission which protests require.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In response to Vladimir Putin's reelection during the Presidential Elections, protesters took to the streets of Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After being denied to demonstrate on Lubyanka Square up to 25,000 people protested in Pushkin Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A couple of thousand protestors stayed behind and clashed with riot police who moved in to disperse them, leading to several hundred arrests, including Alexei Navalny, Sergey Udaltsov and Ilya Yashin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Anti-government protests also took place in St Petersburg too, albeit smaller, at 3,000 people where 300 were arrested.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Another "For Fair Elections" protest was staged on the Novy Arbat street in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A permit was issued for 50,000, but just 25,000 came according to the organisers and 10,000 according to the police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The mood was downbeat after Putin won an absolute majority everywhere but Moscow where he garnered 46.95% of the vote.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Sergei Udaltsov of Left Front, called for a massive demonstration 1 May, but no further protests are scheduled.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Up to 1000 protesters gathered at an unsactioned demonstration at the Ostankino television tower and 94 were arrested.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] They were protesting against a documentary called *The Anatomy of Protest*, which had been shown on 15 March on NTV, a channel owned by Gazprom, a state-run firm.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The documentary claimed that protesters against the election of Putin as president had been given "money and cookies" as payment.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] It also claimed that Alexei Navalny, a well-known opposition blogger, had been "spreading misinformation" and had "too many bodyguards" who were "beating up journalists".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] For the first time since the beginning of the protests, opposition activists were allowed onto Red Square to demonstrate, though they were not allowed to pitch a tent.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Just the previous weekend protesters were barred from the square and arrests made.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] This time, "hundreds" gathered, including Yevgenia Chirikova and Sergei Udaltsov.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After fraud was alleged in the mayoral election of 2012 in Astrakhan and the United Russia candidate was declared the winner, organisers of the 2011–2012 Russian protests supported the defeated candidate, Oleg V.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Shein of Just Russia, in a hunger strike.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Substantial evidence of fraud was cited by the protesters but an official investigation failed to find significant violations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The activists from Moscow found it difficult to gain traction over the issue with local residents who, like most Russians, accept political corruption as a given that is useless to protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The emissaries from Moscow persisted, buoyed by celebrities who support the reform movement, drawing 1,500 to a rally on 14 April.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Protests involving about 20,000 people took place in Moscow the day before Putin's inauguration as President for his third term.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] About 400 protesters were arrested by the police, including Alexei Navalny, Boris Nemtsov and Sergei Udaltsov and 80 were injured.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On the day of the inauguration, at least 120 protesters were arrested in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Police also detained over 100 young men of conscription age (18–27), including 70 who had avoided the military draft.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] From the very beginning, the so-called "March of Millions" was a nervous event.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Even before the march, many large liberal media sites: Echo Moscow radio station, Kommersant daily, and TV Rain channel, were subjected to DDoS-attacks.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Ilya Ponomarev, an opposition leader and member of parliament, said the police had started the clashes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Bolotnaya square filled up and the police sealed it off. when they started to push demonstrators, and people reacted," he said.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Prime Minister Vladimir Putin's press secretary, Dmitry Peskov said he believed the police were being too soft on the protesters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Several hundreds meetings continued on 6/7 night, 7, 7/8 night and 8 May in different places in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The arrests continued in the following months.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The authorities' crackdown on the pro-democratic movement resulted in what has come to be known as the "Bolotnaya square case".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Due to the fractured nature of the opposition, in June 2012 activists decided to create a 45-member Opposition Coordination Council (OCC), which would try to coordinate and direct dissent in Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Elections for the council were held on 20–22 October 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] 170,000 people had registered on the site cvk2012.org, of whom nearly 98,000 were classed as "verified" and nearly 82,000 had cast their votes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Most votes were cast for Alexei Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A peaceful protest rally by tens of thousands, protest organisers estimated their numbers at 50,000, while police put it at 15,000, originating at Pushkin Square was held in Moscow on 12 June 2012, Russia Day.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The rally was preceded by soaking rain; there was a thunderstorm after a few hours.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Protest activities fell within the conditions of the permit which had been issued by the authorities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A call by Sergei Udaltsov to march on the Investigative Committee of Russia which had raided organisers' homes on 11 June was rejected by other protest organisers.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The rally was also the first to follow a new law passed in June 2012 to punish protesters with larger fines.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Participation in the protest was diverse, united only by opposition to Putin; in addition to the revolutionary anti-capitalist Left Front led by Sergei Udaltsov, black-clad Russian nationalists and liberals sporting white ribbons participated despite expressing mutual disdain.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On Saturday afternoon about 2,000 protestors gathered in Lubyanka Square in Moscow, the location of the headquarters of the Federal Security Services, a successor to the KGB.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] A requested permit to lay flowers at the memorial stone in the square was denied.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] There were mass arrests including Alexei Navalny, Sergei Udaltsov of the Left Front, Kseniya Sobchak, and Ilya Yashin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Those arrested, if prosecuted and convicted, face heavy fines under recently enacted legislation which outlaws organising or participating in unauthorised demonstrations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 13 January 2013 a protest called the "March Against Scoundrels" was held in Moscow protesting passage of the Anti-Magnitsky law, a sanctions framework targeted at United States citizens that additionally bans adoption of Russian children by people in the United States.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to the police there were about 10,000 participants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to oppositioners counting there were from 30 to 50 thousand people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to bloggers' counting – 24,474 participants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 6 May 2013 a mass rally took place in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Among featured speakers were Boris Nemtsov and Alexei Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Opposition leaders put the number of attendants at up to 50,000, though police stated 7,000 took part.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 18 July 2013 Alexei Navalny was sentenced to five years in prison for alleged embezzlement.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After the verdict was read, thousands gathered in Moscow's Manezhnaya Square to protest it.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Simultaneously with the anti-government protests, the government and United Russia were supported by rallies of the government funded youth organisations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 4 December, Nashi took to the Moscow streets with 15,000 young people that had been brought to Moscow from more than 20 regions and held meetings and concerts on the Revolution Square and Manezhnaya Square to express their support of president Medvedev and prime minister Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 6 December, about 5,000 activists from Nashi and other pro-Kremlin youth groups held pro-government rallies on Manezhnaya Square and Triumfalnaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] To a New York Times reporter, it seemed that many of the participants in the rally were forced to attend.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 12 December, the 18th anniversary of the Constitution of Russia, thousands of United Russia sympathisers demonstrated in Moscow in support of Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 23 February, Russia's Defender of the Fatherland Day, a massive pro-Putin march took place in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The march ended in Luzhniki Stadium, where a crowd of 130,000 (according to police estimates) was addressed by Vladimir Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The BBC reported, however, that some attendees claimed they had been made to take part or paid.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some said they had been told they were attending a "folk festival".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] After Putin spoke, popular folk band Lubeh took to the stage.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Putin's speech in Luzhniki was his single speech before such a large audience during 2012 presidential campaign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] In the speech he called not to betray the Motherland, but to love her, to unite around Russia and to work together for the good, to overcome the existing problems.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] He said that the foreign interference into Russian affairs should not be allowed, that Russia has its own free will.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On the post-election rally of his supporters at Manezhnaya Square, while making an acceptance speech, Putin was for the first time ever seen with tears in his eyes (later he explained that "it was windy").
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] On 2 December on Sparrow Hills, Sergey Kurginyan and his movement "Sut' Vremeni" (Essence of Time) organised the first protest against what was viewed as "orange" protesters in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The protest also supported the slogan "For Fair Elections".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to the Moscow police, 138,000–150,000 people participated at the protest at the peak of attendance, while more people could have passed through the site.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Opposition groups disputed these figures "as grossly inflated", and some journalists, including one of the state-owned news agency RIA Novosti, said the real number was "much lower".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The infographics from Ria Novosti shows that the Poklonnaya Hill site can provide room for a maximum of 193,000 people at a density of 35 people per 10 sq m, or for 117,000 people at a smaller and more realistic density distribution.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some demonstrators, many of whom were state employees, said they attended under threat of dismissal.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some such claims made in the course of the protest organisation were later refuted as falsifications by the opposition activists and many other demonstrators said they came on their own free will according to a pro-government news site politonline.ru.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Vladimir Putin acknowledged that some attendees could have been coerced, but said that it was impossible to gather so many people by administrative pressure alone.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The participants were mostly middle age, but there were many young and old persons.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some of the participants were bused from other regions and cities with the transport provided by organisations participating in the action.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] At a temperature of −21 °C, a number of heat guns were set up, as well as tents with free hot tea and confectionery.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The resulting large attendance at the protest was not expected, and resulted in a traffic jam in a nearby Kutozovsky Avenue.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The organisers of the protests applied to the Moscow authorities to gather 15,000 people, but since the number was exceeded, they were faced with paying a fine.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Vladimir Putin, who earlier in the evening claimed to share the ideals of those who would go to Poklonnaya Hill, offered to pay part of the fine with his own money.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The "anti-Orange protest" name alludes to the (November 2004 – January 2005) Orange Revolution in Ukraine, the most ill-known to Russians colour revolution.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The term "orange" in Russian political discourse has highly negative connotations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The speakers declared to be against "orangeism", "collapse of the country", "perestroika" and "revolution", reminding the public of such historical events as Gorbachev's Perestroika and the 1917 Russian Revolution and urging never to repeat them.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The call for fair elections was supported, but the leaders of protesters on Bolotnaya Square and Sakharov Avenue were condemned as "successors to those who destroyed the country in 1991 and 1917" and who allegedly want "to remove not Putin, but the Russian state".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The visit of anti-government protest leaders to the U.S. embassy was condemned, as well as the alleged American interference.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Pop-rock singer and composer Denis Maydanov performed on the scene, and pop-rock group Diskoteka Avariya sang their popular song "The Evil Approaches".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The symbol of the "anti-Orange protest" was an orange snake strangled in a fist.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The motto of the protest was "Нам есть, что терять!" (*We have things to lose*).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The top slogan chosen by online vote was "Не дадим развалить страну!" (*Won't allow collapse of the country!*) and among those frequently used were "Мы за стабильность" (*We are for stability*) and "Когда мы едины и мы непобедимы!" (*When we are united we are invincible!*).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to the BBC on 7 December, "State TV channels have generally ignored the protests, covering only pro-government rallies" In contrast, newspapers have mentioned the protests in more depth.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The only federal TV station to mention the protests at length before 10's December was the independent, but not broadcast widely, Ren TV.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] By 10 December, however, breaking with practice in recent years, all the main state-controlled channels were covering the protests, and in a professional and objective manner.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to one Russian media Alexey Pivovarov, NTV-channel host (now tightly run state media), refused to broadcast if the protests are not covered.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Later, in 2013 Pivovarov have left the NTV.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Western media covered the protests extensively starting on 5 December.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Initial coverage by Fox News used footage of the 2011 Athens riots, showing palm trees, people throwing Molotov cocktails at police, and signs in Greek which Fox later claimed was an error and subsequently removed the report from its site.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Twitter users in Russia have reported being overwhelmed by pro-government tweets timed to Bolotnaya Square protest-related tweets.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Many tweets seem to have been sent by hijacked computers, though the perpetrator(s) are not yet known.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] According to a report made by The Wall Street Journal the Russia's Federal Security Service (FSB) have made a formal request to the social media site VKontakte to block opposition groups who 'encourage people to "trash the streets, to organize a revolution".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The request was declined as only a few users behaved violently and it was unjust to ban a whole generally peaceful group.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The two largest protest actions in December 2011 took place on Bolotnaya Square (10 December) and Academician Sakharov Avenue (24 December), and another major protest action is planned on Bolotnaya on 4 February 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The white ribbon emerged in October 2011 as a symbol of opposition and since the elections has picked up momentum.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Some Russians have been tying it to their clothing, cars, and other objects, and the motif has appeared on runet and on Twitter.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] By 10 December, the TV Rain channel was showing a white ribbon by its on-screen logo.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] The station's owner, Natalya Sindeyeva, explained this as being a sign of "sincerity", rather than "propaganda", and an attempt to be "mediators" instead of simply journalists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] NTV described 10 December as the day of "white ribbons".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p01] Vladimir Putin contemptuously referred to the white ribbons used by Russian protesters, comparing them to condoms being used as a symbol of the fight against AIDS.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] President Dmitry Medvedev ordered an investigation into allegations of vote-rigging, though this received a cynical response from many opponents on his Facebook page.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] He also defended the right of people to express their views, while denouncing the street protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] On 22 December 2011, he called for a number of reform steps, including reintroducing the direct election of governors and reducing the required signatures for registering a political party or running in the presidential election.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] A bill reintroducing direct election of governors was introduced in the Duma on 16 January 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] On 27 December 2011, Putin reassigned Vladislav Surkov to the task of advancing Russia's modernisation and development efforts; he remains a deputy prime minister but will no longer oversee Russia's political processes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Medvedev in his state of the nation address made 21 December 2011.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] According to Surkov, "The system has already changed".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] The rights of at least three Western television news channels (the BBC, CNN and Bloomberg) were suspended in Moscow by major provider Akado Telecom on 12 July 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] While the move was not officially linked to the protests, but rather to outdated licences, Alexei Navalny noted that it came just three days after comments by President Putin that "Russia's policies often suffer from a one-sided portrayal these days".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] (United States) Jay Carney, President Barack Obama's second White House Press Secretary, said that anti-government protests in Russia are a "positive sign" for democracy in the country.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Mikhail Gorbachev, former president of the Soviet Union and general secretary of the Soviet Communist Party, has called on the authorities to hold a new election, citing electoral irregularities and ballot box stuffing.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] He criticised Vladimir Putin and the United Russia political party for violating peoples human rights and for not ruling the country in a proper Democratic fashion.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] During the next major round of demonstrations that occurred on 24 December, he called on Putin to resign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] The 2011 protests were the biggest in Russia since the 1990s, and surprised many with their scale.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] According to Victor Shenderovich, an opposition political commentator for radio station Ekho Moskvy, "This is political, not economic.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] The coal miners came out because they were not paid.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] The people coming onto the streets of Moscow are very well off.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] These are people protesting because they were humiliated.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] They were just told, 'Putin is coming back.'" According to Thomas L.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Friedman, *The New York Times* columnist this humiliation of the rising middle class is the common ground the Russian movement shares with the Arab Spring.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] According to *The New York Times*, another "explanation is the high level of public corruption [in Russia], which threatens new personal wealth.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Medvedev" contributed greatly, something some "Russians now snidely refer to [...] as "rokirovka" – the Russian word for castling in chess".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Imprisoned oligarch Mikhail Khodorkovsky has claimed that the protests were inspired, at least in part, by the example of the Arab Spring.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] He told *The Guardian*, "We have only to reflect on the events in countries swept up in the Arab Spring to recognise the transformation taking place in the compact between the rulers and the ruled.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] 8 June 2012 in response to increased militancy by a segment of the protest movement a law was enacted imposing severe penalties on protesters who engage in unauthorised demonstrations or who exceed the boundaries of authorised ones.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Maximum penalties were fines of several thousand rubles or imposed labour of up to 200 hours.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] On 11 June 2012, the day before a scheduled protest in Moscow the homes of the prominent activists, Kseniya Sobchak, Alexei Navalny, Sergei Udaltsov and others were raided and extensively searched.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] Literature, electronic data, lists of supporters, and funds were seized.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2011-2013-russian-protests-p02] The activists were ordered to report to the Investigative Committee of Russia for questioning during the scheduled protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The anti-corruption protests began in March 2017 but were joined by and overlapped the 2018 Russian pension protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The anti-corruption protests were primarily led by Alexei Navalny, who was joined by well-known participants such as the Libertarian Party, Open Russia, and Artpodgotovka.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] They occurred as a result of the 2014–2016 Russian financial crisis aftermath, although they had their root in the corruption at the different levels up to the highest echelons of the Russian power.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The protests and demonstrations against corruption in the Russian government began in March 2017 after the release of the investigative film *He Is Not Dimon to You* by Navalny's Anti-Corruption Foundation, which had garnered more than 23 million views on YouTube.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Discontentment was triggered by the alleged corrupt activity of Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev as presented in the film, the inadequately planned demolition of apartments in Moscow and the protracted strikes of truck drivers related to the Platon toll system, which had been ongoing since 2015.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] National protests against corruption in Russia took place simultaneously in more than 100 cities across the country on 26 March 2017.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A new wave of mass protests occurred on 12 June 2017.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] After the arrest of Navalny on 29 September, hours before a planned rally in Nizhny Novgorod, a new wave of protests was announced for 7 October, the birthday of Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protests and uprisings continued in 2018, with the tendency to radicalization, and a record number of protesters was detained on 5 May, two days before Putin's inauguration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Mass rallies were held in more than 60 cities across Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In March 2017, Alexei Navalny and his Anti-Corruption Foundation launched the campaign *He Is Not Dimon To You*, accusing Dmitry Medvedev, the prime minister and former president of Russia, of corruption.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The authorities both ignored the report produced by Navalny and commented that the report was issued by a "convicted criminal" and was not worth commenting on.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] On 26 March, Navalny organized a series of anti-corruption rallies in different cities across Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] This appeal was responded to by the representatives of 95 of Russian cities, and four cities abroad: London, Prague, Basel and Bonn.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In some cities, the rallies were sanctioned by the authorities, but in others, including Saint Petersburg, they were prohibited.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Moscow authorities declined the event request by Navalny in the city centre, but did not suggest any alternative location.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Navalny referred to a decision of the Constitutional court and declared the event for being permitted.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The Moscow police said that 500 people had been detained, but according to the human rights group OVD-Info, 1,030 people were detained in Moscow alone, including Navalny himself.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The Main Department of the Ministry of Internal Affairs posted a message on its official website with a call to Moscow residents not to join the event.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] It said that the action in Moscow was not coordinated with the municipality and was illegal.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] On 26 March, an estimated 60,000 people took part in anti-corruption protests across 80 Russian towns and cities and hundreds of protesters were detained, including opposition leader Alexei Navalny and employees of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] According to Human Rights Watch, Russian authorities have harassed, intimidated, or threatened to expel schoolchildren and university students who participated in anti-corruption demonstrations on 26 March.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] 70 children were arrested in Moscow alone.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Action organized by the Open Russia civic movement led by Mikhail Khodorkovsky took place in dozens of cities all across Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Action was called "Fed up with" ("Nadoel" in Russian) with the aim to urge for changes in Russian political rule.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protestors called for Putin and government to resign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In Saint Petersburg, Tyumen, Kemerovo, Tula and several other cities rallies were suppressed by police, with a total of 200 people being detained countrywide.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A new wave of protests with the same goals was announced by Navalny on spring.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] According to Reuters and rights groups, tens of thousands of protesters attended and more than one thousand were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A Moscow court sentenced Navalny to 30 days in prison for calling people to the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] White House spokesman Sean Spicer condemned the arrest of protesters and called for their release.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Russian authorities rejected US petitions and criticised the widening on the sanctions against Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protest actions against corruption in the highest echelons of the Russian government were held on 7 October 2017, on the day of the 65th anniversary of V.V.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Putin in the form of rallies, processions and single pickets in 79 cities of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] At the rallies came from 2560 to 21,520 people, like the supporters of Alexei Navalny, and his opponents.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In Saint Petersburg, the action began on the Field of Mars, and in Moscow on Tverskaya Street.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The reason for their conduct were facts of corruption V.V.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] More than 260 participants of the action were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In Moscow, many police were present, the Okhotny Ryad station was closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The police conducted selective searches of citizens, many were taken away in padded wagons.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] At 13:00 on the message OVD-Info in Moscow, 82 people were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] 2 people were detained in Saint Petersburg, 4 in Krasnoyarsk.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Also detained a representative of the "Echo of Moscow".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Later in Saint Petersburg, another 10 people were detained near the Smolny Institute.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] At 21:00 on the message OVD-Info, the number of detainees increased to 448 people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Most of the detentions took place in Moscow – 339, in Saint Petersburg 21 people, according to unconfirmed reports, 49 of them – minors.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] It remains to spend the night in the police departments, on the night of 6 November, about 112 people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protests within the framework of the "Strike of voters" were held on 28 January 2018 in the form of rallies, processions and solitary pickets in 118 cities of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The reason was the refusal of the CEC to register at the election of Alexei Navalny, after which he announced a protest on 28 January, and urged all his supporters not to come to the elections and agitate others not to take part in them.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The Ministry of Internal Affairs estimated the number of participants in the shares of 3500–4500 people, the HROs – in 5000.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] According to the supporters of Alexei Navalny, the participants were much more.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The New Times, referring to eyewitnesses, reported 4,000–5,000 protesters in Moscow and 2,000–3,000 in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In Yekaterinburg, in an agreed action, Mayor Yevgeny Roizman and Navaly Head of Staff Leonid Volkov took part and spoke at the rally.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The presidential candidate, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, spoke with several protestors on Tverskaya Street in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] According to various estimates, about 15,000 people took part in the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Approximately 13,000 people gathered in Moscow central Sakharov square for a protest rally to urge government to unblock Telegram Messenger.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The app was blocked by Roscomnadzor, Russian media authorities who claimed it was used to coordinate terror attacks.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protesters denounced the block as the censorship act and freedom of speech violation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Mass protest actions and rallies took place in 90 towns and cities over the country against Vladimir Putin fourth inauguration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Alexei Navalny in his blog compared Vladimir Putin with a tsar.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] More than thousand people were arrested countrywide.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The majority of people were detained in Moscow, Saint-Petersburg, Chelyabinsk, Yakutsk, Krasnodar, Tolyatti, Krasnoyarsk, Voronezh, Astrakhan, Penza, Kaluga, Belgorod, Novokuznetsk, Vladimir and Samara.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] From July, almost every weekend, protest rallies and demonstrations were organized against the planned retirement age hike.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Such events occurred in nearly all major cities countrywide including Novosibirsk, St.-Petersburg and Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Total number of participants exceeded 200 thousands, with maximal single-event attendance of about 15 thousands (in Moscow).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] These events were coordinated by all opposition parties with the leading role of the communists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Also trade unions and some individual politicians (among whom Navalny) functioned as organizers of the public actions.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The most noticeable street rallies, related with the retirement-age reform, proceeded on 1 July, 18, 28 July-29 July, 2 September and 9 September 2018.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] So, on 2 September, large-scale anti-reform manifestations were led by the Russian communists and some other left-wing oppositional political forces.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A week later, on 9 September, the rallies were organized by Alexei Navalny all over Russia, over 800 people were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The Anti-Corruption Foundation building was evacuated due to a bomb message, interrupting the webcast of the protest conducted from the office.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Soon the staff of the Foundation were detained by police, who also began to conduct searches and seizure of equipment.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Some time later, Alexei Navalny was charged with organizing an unlawful meeting.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] An ACF employee and the head of the Moscow branch of the unregistered "Party of progress" Nikolay Lyaskin was detained for 25 days.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Leonid Volkov, the head of Alexei Navalny's presidential campaign, was charged with extremism.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] An April 2017 Levada poll found that 45% of surveyed Russians support the resignation of Russian Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, while 33% opposed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] *Newsweek* reported that "An opinion poll by the Moscow-based Levada Center indicated that 38 percent of Russians supported the rallies and that 67 percent held Putin personally responsible for high-level corruption".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A May 2017 Levada poll found that 58% of surveyed Russians supported the protests, while 23% said they disapprove.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In May, Yury Kuly was sentenced to 8 months in jail, and on 24 May Alexander Shpakov was sentenced for 1.5 years in jail, both for alleged violence against the police on the 26 March rally in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Protests, meeting and pickets have been erupted in 79-154 towns and cities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Some protests ended with mass arrests and clashes with police (such as Moscow, Saint-Petersburg, Chelyabinsk, Yekaterinburg).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In Moscow on 26 March 2017, an estimated 20,000 protesters gathered, with at least 500 arrested according to police, while the human rights group OVD-Info counted over 800 detained in Moscow alone.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Seventeen employees of Navalny's Anti-Corruption Foundation were also arrested.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] On 5 May, an estimated 2,000 to 5,000 protests have taken to the streets, protesters clashed with police, which resulted in arrests of 164 to 200.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Russian state television completely ignored the protests on Sunday.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Monday morning's bulletins were similarly blank.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Pro-Kremlin newspapers also ignored the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Across the country, students have reported being press-ganged into lectures warning them of the perils of supporting those opposed to Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Some schools and universities have simply tasked teachers with persuading their students not to go to protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] A 13-year old student was quoted as saying: "They don't have the right to 'reeducate' us, to change our political views.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] I think they're doing this because they're afraid.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Alisa Vox, a Russian singer, appeared in the video for "Baby Boy", posted online on 15 May.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] It has amassed more than 2.1 million views and more than a quarter of a million 'dislikes', or downvotes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] Navalny said Vox's video was a Russian government PR stunt to dissuade his supporters that she had received money for.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] In many cities, on the day of the protest, the public transport route was specially changed so that it was more difficult for people to get to the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2017-2018-russian-protests] The protest actions on 12 June 7 October, 5 November 2017 and 28 January 2018 were not mentioned at all on state-owned TV channels and the media.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The **2021 Russian protests**, also known as **Navalny Protests**, began on 23 January 2021 in support of the opposition leader Alexei Navalny after he was immediately detained upon returning to Russia after being sent to Germany for treatment following his poisoning the previous year.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Days before protests began, a film by Navalny and his Anti-Corruption Foundation (FBK) called *Putin's Palace*, which revolves around the connection between president Vladimir Putin and a palace allegedly being built for him, was released.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On the first day, protests were held in 122 towns and cities across Russia in what were one of the largest anti-government demonstrations since protests were held against the results of legislative elections in 2011 and Putin's re-election in 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Unsanctioned by the authorities, the protests were met with police crackdowns, with thousands detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] As a result, Navalny's team announced a suspension of street protests on 4 February, stating that they would focus on legislative elections that would be held later in the year, and later announcing a shift from street protests to courtyard protests to avoid direct confrontation with police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In response to Navalny's deterioration of health while in prison, street protests were held again on 21 April for the last time.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Despite the protests, Navalny's suspended sentence of three and a half years was replaced with a prison sentence on 2 February.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In March 2022, Navalny was sentenced to an additional nine years in prison after being found guilty of embezzlement and contempt of court in a new trial.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny had been hospitalized on 20 August 2020, in serious condition after he was poisoned with a Novichok nerve agent during a flight from Tomsk to Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He was medically evacuated to Berlin and discharged on 22 September.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The use of a Novichok nerve agent was confirmed by the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Though the Kremlin denied involvement in his poisoning, the EU and the UK responded by imposing sanctions on six senior Russian officials and a state chemical centre.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny accused president Vladimir Putin of being responsible for his poisoning.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] An investigation by Bellingcat and *The Insider* implicated agents from the Federal Security Service (FSB) in Navalny's poisoning.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny returned to Russia on 17 January 2021, where he was immediately detained on accusations of violating terms of a suspended jail sentence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Investigative Committee of Russia also said that it was investigating Navalny for alleged fraud.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A court decision the next day ordered the detention of Navalny until 15 February for violating his parole.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A makeshift court was set up in the police station where Navalny was being held.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Another hearing would later be held to determine whether his suspended sentence should be replaced with a jail term.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny described the procedure as “ultimate lawlessness”.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also called on his supporters to take to the streets, saying: “Do not be silent.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Take to the streets – not for me, but for you”.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny's regional network head, Leonid Volkov, said that preparations were being made for protests to be organised across the country on 23 January.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] While in jail, an investigation by Navalny and his Anti-Corruption Foundation (FBK) was published on 19 January, accusing Putin of corruption involving the construction of a palace by the Black Sea known as "Putin's Palace".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The video of the investigation also urged people to take to the streets.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Before the protests had begun, the video on YouTube received over 60 million views.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] By the next day the state communications watchdog Roskomnadzor was demanding the social networks VKontakte (VK) and TikTok to stop the spread of calls to the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The efficacy of these calls is disputed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Arrests of several of Navalny's aides and allies, including Lyubov Sobol, began on 21 January.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Several were jailed or fined on charges of disobeying police orders or organizing a public event without notifying the authorities, with Sobol being fined and released.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Ministry of Internal Affairs also threatened to prosecute those spreading calls to join the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Prosecutor General's Office also ordered the censor, Roskomnadzor, to block access to pages that call for unauthorized rallies.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 22 January, the Main Directorate of the Ministry of Internal Affairs for Moscow issued a statement warning against calls to the protests or participation in them.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] It stated that any attempts to hold unauthorized events as well as “provocative actions by the participants” would be regarded as a “threat to public order” and be “immediately suppressed”.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Social media networks began removing information about the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] VK blocked access to a number of pages on the protests, with the pages stating that it was blocked on the requirement of the General Prosecutor's Office.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Roskomnadzor also stated that VK, Instagram, TikTok and YouTube blocked some content which involved “calls for children to participate in illegal mass events”.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] However, Facebook and YouTube have countered this claim.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Facebook said it “received requests from the local regulator to restrict access to certain content that calls for protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Reuters estimated up to 40,000 protesters gathered in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Authorities gave a figure of only 4,000 participants, while other estimates included 15,000 and 25,000 participants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters began gathering at Tverskaya Street and Pushkinskaya Square, with a procession ending near Matrosskaya Tishina where Navalny was being held.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Riot police in the city began breaking up the protest and detaining participants before it was scheduled to start.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Alexei Navalny's wife, Yulia Navalnaya, was detained by police at the exit of Moscow's Teatralnaya metro station; she was released after being detained for 3 hours.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny's ally, Lyubov Sobol, was also detained shortly after arriving at Pushkinskaya Square and was later fined.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Clashes between police and protesters broke out.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Tsvetnoy Boulevard, an FSB car was stopped by a crowd of protesters and hit with snowballs, with state media reporting that the driver of the car sustained an eye injury.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] State media reported that around 40 police officers were injured.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Investigative Committee said that it opened a probe into instances of violence against police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Russian rapper Noize MC, rapper Vladi from the group Kasta, director Vasily Sigarev, writer Dmitry Bykov and others attended the protest in Pushkinskaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to *Kommersant*, about 5,000 protesters gathered in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to MBKh Media, around 10,000 people took part in the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters gathered at Senate Square and moved towards Nevsky Prospekt and the Kazan Cathedral, then the Field of Mars, where police began to disperse the protesters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A video of a riot policeman kicking a woman in the stomach was circulated online.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The woman was later reportedly taken to intensive care.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The police apologized for the incident and it was reported that the Ministry of Internal Affairs opened a probe.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, over 500 people in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Estimates of the number of protesters in Perm varied between 3,000 and 10,000.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to MBKh Media, around 2,500 people attended the protest in Ufa, Bashkortostan, around 5,000 people attended the protest in Chelyabinsk, around 3,000 people attended the protest in Samara and around 3,000 people attended the protest in Arkhangelsk.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Kazan, around 3,000–4,000 people were estimated to have gathered at the protest which started on Bauman Street.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Kaliningrad, up to 3,000 people were estimated to have taken part in the protest, which moved towards Victory Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Krasnodar, around 5,000–7,000 people were estimated to have taken part in the protest, with over 50 people detained according to OVD-Info.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Siberia, around 4,000 protesters gathered in Novosibirsk according to Tayga.info.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Thousands walked from the city's House of Officers to Lenin Square in the city center.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police broke up the protest using force and blocked the main street.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, around 100 people in the city were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Irkutsk, several thousand people took part in the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Estimates of the number of protesters in Yekaterinburg varied between 3,000 and 10,000.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The regional authorities gave an estimate of 3,000 while the local headquarters of Navalny's team gave an estimate of 10,000 participants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to Znak, around 5,000 people attended.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The former mayor of the city and opposition politician Yevgeny Roizman and City Duma deputy Konstantin Kiselev attended the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Riot police began breaking up the protest and clashes between police and protesters broke out, with officers hit with snowballs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In the Russian Far East, up to 3,000 protesters gathered in Vladivostok, according to *Novaya Gazeta*.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Russian YouTuber Yury Dud attended the protest in the city, however told journalists that he came there for "musical, cultural and friendly affairs".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters moved towards the central square before being dispersed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to *Novaya Gazeta*, around 1,000 protesters gathered in Khabarovsk by Lenin Square in support of both Navalny and the arrested former governor Sergey Furgal before police dispersed the crowd and started detaining participants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Yakutsk, where temperatures reached −50 °C, several hundred protesters gathered in the city's main square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, over 60 people were detained in Khabarovsk, over 30 people were detained in Vladivostok and 30 people were detained in Yakutsk.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In some Russian cities, there were internet and mobile phone network outages.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Communication issues were reported in cities including Moscow, St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg, Krasnodar, Tyumen, Chelyabinsk, Yekaterinburg, Voronezh, Rostov-on-Don, and Saratov.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Twitter users in Russia also reported problems accessing the network.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 4,002 people across the country were detained that day with over 1,500 of them in Moscow, according to OVD-Info.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 1 Internationally recognised as part of Ukraine, see political status of Crimea and annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation for details.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Leonid Volkov, co-founder of Russia of the Future party, said that Navalny's team plans to organize more protests on 31 January, and then, on every subsequent Saturday or Sunday until their demands are met (somewhat similar to what is happening in Belarus since August 2020).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Volkov also said that the next protests would be held outside the headquarters of the FSB at Lubyanka Square, as well as at Staraya Square, where the offices of the presidential administration are located.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He said the organizers had decided to gather protesters outside the FSB building because they are the "poisoners" and the offices of the presidential administration because they "make the decisions about whether to jail or release Navalny".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A Russian TikToker and his friends were detained for allegedly vandalizing an FSB car in Moscow during the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A widely circulated video showed protesters attacking the car, with state media reporting that the driver was hospitalized with a serious eye injury.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 26 January, it was reported that 20 criminal cases were opened by the Investigative Committee following the protests, with the majority of them under violence against authorities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 28 January, the Investigative Committee also opened a criminal case against Volkov under "persuading minors to commit unlawful acts".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A woman who was kicked by a riot policeman during the protest in a widely circulated video was hospitalized again after her condition worsened.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] After she was released from hospital the day after the protest, she said she accepted the apology from the officer, who visited her in hospital, however she later said she did so because she wanted to be left alone.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg prosecutor's office said it was investigating the incident, while Vyacheslav Volodin, the Chairman of the State Duma, defended the police officer, saying he was "being prevented from performing his duties".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Russian police days later searched Navalny's apartment according to Navalny's team, ahead of another nationwide protest on 31 January.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny's brother Oleg was present in the apartment, who was taken away by the police following the search.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The FBK also said that officers searched its headquarters and the "Navalny Live" studio, as well as the apartment of Kira Yarmysh and Navalny's doctor Anastasia Vasilyeva.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The head of the FBK, Ivan Zhdanov, said that the Ministry of Internal Affairs carried out the searches within the framework of Article 236 of the Criminal Code of Russia related to violations of sanitary and epidemiological standards.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny's coordinator in Nizhny Novgorod, Roman Tregubov, was arrested on 28 January and the next day was sentenced to five days in jail.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 30 January, the day before protests would begin again, a video of him was published where he announced his resignation and urged people not to go to the protests.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Other videos by the Investigative Committee were also published earlier featuring apologies by detained protesters who allegedly attacked law enforcement.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The FSB building in Lubyanka Square was also cordoned off.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protest organizers changed the start of the rally to the Sukharevskaya and Krasnye Vorota metro stations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police began detaining protesters by the stations, and the entrances and exits to the stations were then closed at the request of the police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The location was then changed to Komsomolskaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The entrance and exit to the Krasnoselskaya and Sokolniki stations were then closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters then moved towards Matrosskaya Tishina, where Navalny was being held.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Alexei Navalny's wife, Yulia Navalnaya, was detained again after attending the protest in Sokolniki; she was released several hours later and a protocol on violation of the protest law was drawn up against her.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] After police began mass arrests and dispersed protesters outside Matrosskaya Tishina, protesters returned to Komsomolskaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police then blocked off Olkhovskaya Street, trapping protesters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Opposition politician Ilya Yashin was detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg, protest organizers moved the rally to Pionerskaya Square after authorities closed off Nevsky Prospekt.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters gathered near the Bryantsev Youth Theatre.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The rapper Oxxxymiron attended the city's protest on his birthday and was later detained by police; he was later released.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters then moved to Sennaya Square where clashes between police and protesters broke out, and police used tear gas after protesters tried to rescue detainees.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police also reportedly used stun guns and a video of a police officer taking out his pistol and pointing it was published.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] After the dispersal of the protesters on Pionerskaya Square, protesters went along Zagorodny Prospekt towards Moskovsky Prospekt.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters then moved to outside the building of the city's legislative assembly, where they clashed with police and were forcibly dispersed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters then moved back near the Bryantsev Youth Theatre where organizers announced the end of the rally and protesters were finally dispersed by police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Nizhny Novgorod, the National Guard and police blocked Minin and Pozharsky Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Gorkovskaya metro station was also closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Detentions of protesters began in the afternoon on Bolshaya Pokrovskaya Street, near the former Oktyabr cinema.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The journalist Alexander Pichugin was also detained there.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The protesters left the street and began to gather in Minin and Pozharsky Square near the monument to Kuzma Minin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] OMON and police pushed the protesters out of the square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Yekaterinburg, most metro stations were closed (from Prospekt Kosmonavtov to Ploshchad 1905 Goda).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The former mayor of the city, Yevgeny Roizman, participated in the city's protest again despite a warning from the prosecutor's office.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Around 7,000 protesters gathered in the city according to media estimates.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to Tayga.info, around 6,000 protesters gathered in Novosibirsk, more than in the previous protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The state communications watchdog, Roskomnadzor, warned media outlets about heavy fines for "spreading fakes concerning unauthorized rallies", including publishing "inflated figures on the number of participants in illegal rallies".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, 5,611 people were detained, with over 1,800 of them in Moscow and over 1,300 of them in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Also according to OVD-Info, at least 82 journalists were detained.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Several demonstrators were hospitalized due to injuries such as bone fracture.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A deaf-mute Saint Petersburg man was fined for "chanting slogans".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Supporters of Navalny gathered outside the Moscow City Court, where the court was considering a request from the Federal Penitentiary Service (FSIN) to replace Navalny's suspended sentence with a jail sentence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny was charged with violating a suspended sentence he received in 2014 while he was in Germany, a sentence that the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) in 2017 previously ruled as "arbitrary and unreasonable".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, 354 people were detained at the time, including four in Izhevsk.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The court ruled that Navalny's three-and-a-half-year suspended sentence was to be replaced with a prison sentence, minus the amount of time he spent under house arrest, meaning he would spend over two and a half years in a penal colony.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Following the verdict, Navalny's team called for immediate protests near the Kremlin at Manezhnaya Square in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Large numbers of riot police were deployed to the square and other areas in central Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police then cordoned off Manezhnaya Square and Pushkinskaya Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Okhotny Ryad, Teatralnaya and Ploshchad Revolyutsii metro stations were then also closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Around a thousand protesters gathered at Tverskaya Street and two thousand were estimated to have marched down Petrovskiy Pereulok.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The main group of protesters then headed to Pushkin Square.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police dispersed the protesters with force and there were instances of police violence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg, the Gostiny Dvor and Nevsky Prospekt metro stations were closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Mayakovskaya and Ploshchad Vosstaniya metro stations were also later closed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, 1,463 people in total were detained, including over 1,180 in Moscow and 280 in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 4 February, Leonid Volkov, Navalny's chief of staff, announced that protests would be suspended until at least spring to focus on the parliamentary elections in autumn.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He said: "If we go out every week, thousands more will be detained, and hundreds more beaten...
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The work of the regional headquarters will be paralyzed and it will be impossible to work on elections.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Alexei has asked us to concentrate on this autumn".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also said that his team would work on getting Navalny out of prison using "foreign policy methods" including working to ensure that foreign leaders put pressure on Putin and his government to release Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 6 February, the Russian government expelled three diplomats, each from Germany, Poland and Sweden for allegedly participating in the protests on 23 January, leading to protest from the United States and EU leaders.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 8 February, the governments of Germany, Poland, and Sweden each expelled a Russian diplomat in retaliation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 8 February, a Saratov lawmaker from the Communist Party, Nikolai Bondarenko, was detained on charges of violating protest rules.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] His colleagues said he attended the protests on 31 January as an observer.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Olga Alimova, the Saratov regional branch leader of the Communist Party, linked Bondarenko's detention with his stated plans to run for the State Duma elections later in the year, where he would compete with State Duma speaker Vyacheslav Volodin and is considered a strong challenger.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The leader of the Communist Party, Gennady Zyuganov, said he would defend him in court and fight for his release.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 9 February, Volkov announced new courtyard protests on 14 February in what he said was a "completely different format", shifting from street protests to avoid direct confrontation with police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Volkov invited supporters to gather in courtyards and hold up their phones with the flashlight on during the evening.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Volkov stated: "Hundreds of thousands of people took to the Russian streets on 23 January and 31 January.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The response was an unprecedented wave of violence and repression...
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] We need to find a way to overcome it and hold an event that riot police could not prevent and everyone could attend".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also addressed his earlier remarks on protests being suspended, saying: "My poorly worded phrase was interpreted by everyone that the protests are cancelled.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Dmitry Peskov, upon being questioned whether or not such actions would be considered illegal, was quoted saying: "We won't be playing cat and mouse with them".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 11 February, Russian federal prosecutors warned against participation and incitement of unauthorized mass demonstrations, threatening felony charges against Internet users who advocated "riots".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A number of actions against repression were held in Russia on Valentine's Day.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In the action called "Love is stronger than fear" organized by Navalny's team, courtyard protests were held across Russia during the evening.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A medic who worked at a coronavirus hospital in Moscow posted a widely-shared photo of him taking part in the flashlight protest, however said that he was fired the next day, saying "this is what they do to all dissenters in Russia".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Moscow, hundreds of women formed a "chain of solidarity" along Arbat Street to support Navalny's wife and female victims of repression, taking inspiration from the women-led protests held in Belarus.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Despite not being authorized, there was no police presence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg at Voskresenskaya Naberezhnaya.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] An authorized rally against repression was held in Kazan at Millennium Square, organized by representatives of Yabloko, PARNAS, and Left Front.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Authorities permitted up to 200 participants, citing coronavirus restrictions, however *Kommersant* reported that around 1,000 people attended the rally.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Protesters demanded the release of political prisoners including Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, 19 people in total were detained that day.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said that there were no mass arrests because the pro-Navalny actions were held without breaking the law.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In March, Alexey Navalny's team launched a campaign for his release called "Freedom for Navalny!" where those who live in Russia may pledge to participate in an upcoming protest on the website of Navalny's team.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Once the amount of pledges reach 500,000, Navalny's team will announce a date for the upcoming mass demonstration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 18 April, Navalny's team announced new protests nationwide for 21 April, saying that Navalny was being killed in prison and while the goal was to reach 500,000 pledges (with the number of pledges reaching over 450,000 that day), it was not possible to wait any longer.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The date coincided with Putin's Presidential Address to the Federal Assembly.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Prior to assigned start time of the nationwide protests, 19:00 Moscow time, many people had already begun protesting, with the largest demonstrations being in Irkutsk and Novosibirsk.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 186 people were detained as of 17:00 Moscow time, with that number rising to 221 by 18:00.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Within that time, large-scale demonstrations had begun in Irkutsk, Novosibirsk, Perm, and Yekaterinburg, with protests beginning to flare up in Moscow and Saint Petersburg, and police setting up barricades in many of the aforementioned cities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In Saint Petersburg, videos were recorded of protestors chanting "Putin is a killer".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Soon after the protests began, around 400 people across Russia were detained by the police.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Around that time the number of protesters in Moscow and St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg had grown heavily, particularly in Tverskaya Street in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] By that time Alexei Navalny's wife, Yulia Navalnaya, had joined the protesters in Moscow, followed by Alexei Navalny's brother, Oleg, some time later.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Police gave a figure of 6,000 protesters in Manezhnaya Square, while independent observers and local media gave substantially higher estimates.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petersburg, the police began mass detaining protesters in Sennaya Square around 20:29 MSK.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] By that time the MVD gave a figure of 4,500 protesters in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] As the police mass detained protesters in Sennaya Square, the police managed to disperse the crowd, only for the crowd to relocate to Rubinstein Street.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to OVD-Info, 1,985 people were detained, with 839 of them detained in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 23 April, Alexei Navalny announced that he would end his 24-day hunger strike, following his examination conducted by civilian doctors not affiliated with the Corrective Colony in Pokrov who had warned that he could die if he continued his hunger strike.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also praised the protests and the support he received from around the world, while also noting solidarity hunger strikes conducted by some of Navalny's supporters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny also noted that the process of ending the hunger strike would also take 24 days.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 27 April, two journalists from the independent news outlets Ekho Moskvy and TV Rain were detained by police in their homes after covering the protests on 21 April, with one being released and ordered to appear for questioning later.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 12 May, opposition politician and former mayor of Yekaterinburg, Yevgeny Roizman, was sentenced to nine days in jail for "organizing an unsanctioned event" on 31 January and 21 April through his Twitter account.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The next day, the sentence was reduced to 24 hours after an appeal by his lawyers.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Roizman was also ordered to 30 hours of compulsory labor.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 13 May, Volkov stated that future protests would not be staged in advance and would instead be "unprepared", citing a persecution of protest organizers and protesters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On 9 June, Navalny's political network, including his headquarters and the FBK, were designated as extremist organizations and liquidated by the Moscow City Court.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov accused the United States of interfering in Russian domestic affairs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The U.S. embassy sent an alert warning American citizens about the location of protests in Moscow and U.S. officials also criticized the police crackdown.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Peskov also downplayed the scale of the protests, saying "few people came out" and that "many people vote for Putin".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The Russian Foreign Ministry also summoned the U.S. ambassador over the demonstration alert.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] It was reported that Deputy Foreign Minister Sergei Ryabkov informed U.S.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Ambassador John Sullivan that Russia considered the alerts to be "direct interference in the internal affairs of our country".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] After protests began on 31 January, the Foreign Ministry again accused the United States of meddling in Russian internal affairs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] President Vladimir Putin, after being asked about his thoughts on the protests during a videoconference with students on Students Day, said that "everyone has the right to express their point of view within the legal framework.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Anything outside the law is not just counterproductive, but also dangerous".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny's chief of staff, Leonid Volkov, called the protests a "victory over fear" and a "real nationwide movement that unites a wide variety of people".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also said that "we are not dissidents" and that "we are fighting for the political majority".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to a poll by the Levada Center carried out from 29 January to 2 February 2021, 21% of Russian respondents said they followed the protests closely, 59% said they heard about it, and 19% said they did not hear anything about it.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 22% of respondents felt positive about the protests, 37% felt neutral, and 39% felt negative.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 45% and 43% of respondents said that they expected further growth in protest activity with political demands or economic demands, respectively – the highest rate since 1998.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] However, only 15% and 17% expressed willingness to take part in political protests or economic protests, respectively – a drop compared to the last poll in November 2020.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] According to a poll by the same pollster published on 13 May 2021, 11% of Russian respondents said they followed the 21 April protests closely, 61% said they heard about it, and 28% said they did not hear anything about it.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] 16% of respondents had positive attitudes to the 21 April protests, 42% were neutral, and 39% had negative attitudes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The human rights organisation OVD-Info created a petition against the "Fortress" plan, which was introduced in police sites in order to ban visits to the police department by "unauthorized persons", which, in turn, prevents the direct meeting of lawyers with their detainees.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A number of petitions including by Novaya Gazeta and Amnesty International were also created demanding for Navalny's freedom.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A petition by Novaya Gazeta demanded a change to the law on rallies and demonstrations in accordance with the Constitution of the Russian Federation and to guarantee citizens the right of peaceful assembly.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The petition by Novaya Gazeta demanding for Navalny's release was signed by over 200,000 people, including numerous celebrities and public figures.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Amnesty International published a request for collective assistance in writing appeals in order to achieve justice in the case of Margarita Yudina, who was beaten during the protest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Petitions to bring to justice the security official who committed the violence was also filed by the Libertarian Party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A petition by Amnesty International that was signed by over 200,000 people was sent to the Kremlin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In addition, several petitions were created demanding for the release of a Chechen protester, Said-Magomed Dzhumaev, who clashed with security forces in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Marina Litvinenko, the widow of Alexander Litvinenko, created a petition calling for the Nobel Peace Prize to be awarded to Alexei Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] State Department spokesman Ned Price condemned what he called "harsh tactics against protesters and journalists" and called on the Russian authorities to "release all those detained for exercising their universal rights".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also urged Russia to "fully cooperate with the international community's investigation into the poisoning of Aleksey Navalny and credibly explain the use of a chemical weapon on its soil".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The EU's High Representative Josep Borrell said that he would press for the release of Navalny when he visits Moscow on 5 February 2021, saying that it would be "a good opportunity to discuss with my Russian counterpart all relevant issues, to pass clear messages on the current situation".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] EU foreign ministers debated sanctions on Russia however held off new sanctions for the time being.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] British Foreign Secretary Dominic Raab condemned what he called was "the Russian authorities' use of violence against peaceful protesters and journalists".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He also called on the Russian government to "release citizens detained during peaceful demonstrations".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The British Foreign Ministry in a statement said that it was "deeply concerned by the detention of peaceful protesters" and that it was continuing to "monitor the situation closely".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Japanese Foreign Minister Toshimitsu Motegi urged the Russian government to release Navalny, calling for "transparency and bring the perpetrators' of Navalny's poisoning to justice.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Motegi also states that "The Japanese government is closely watching (the situation) with concern.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Navalny and those who have been detained arbitrarily while engaging in peaceful demonstrations".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] New York Rangers winger Artemi Panarin expressed his support for Navalny, and shortly after took absentee of leave following allegations he assaulted an 18-year old Russian in 2011.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] He states he believes the allegations are politically motivated.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Solidarity protests were also held in cities around the world on 23 January 2021, including Berlin, Munich, Paris, Prague, Kraków, Helsinki, London, Tallinn, The Hague, Denver, Vienna, Tel Aviv, Copenhagen, Melbourne, Sydney, Montreal and Tokyo.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The solidarity movement of Russian communities abroad further expanded, as a total of around 3,000 participated in rallies across several major European cities as well as Philadelphia and San Francisco.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] Rallies in support of Navalny were held in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] A rally in Sydney included people who disagreed with the protesters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] In solidarity with Navalny's hunger strike protests were held in a range of Russian and international cities among which are Rome, Riga, Tbilisi, London, Berlin, Hagatna and Tel Aviv.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] On the US island of Guam, a protest took place against the autocratic rule of Vladimir Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/2021-russian-protests] The action took place at the Legislature in Hagatna, symbolizing a veto on Putin's message to the Federal Assembly.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] The **5th of December Party** (Russian: Партия 5 декабря, romanized: *Partiya pyatogo dekabrya*) is a Russian liberal unregistered political party, managed by the Federal Coordinating Council (FCC).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] Among the co-founders of the party are Roman Dobrokhotov, Konstantin Yankauskas, Denis Bilunov, Sergey Davidis, Natalia Pelevine (later left the party) and others.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] The party participated in the elections to the Opposition Coordination Council in October 2012.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] According to their results, the council included three members of the party: Sergey Davidis, Pyotr Tsarkov and Anna Karetnikova.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] The name of the party is associated with the day the protests began on Bolotnaya Square, with disagreement with the official results of the Parliamentary elections to the State Duma of the 6th convocation, which took place on December 4, 2011.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] The next day, December 5, were protests against the United Russia took place.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] In addition, December 5 is the date of the first Glasnost meeting in post-war Soviet Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On December 8, 2011, the Constituent Congress of the All-Russian political party "5th of December Party" was held in Moscow, at which the highest governing body of the party, instead of a single leader, established the "Federal Coordination Council" (FCC).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On June 7, 2013, "5th of December Party" submitted documents for registration to the Ministry of Justice.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On June 27, the Ministry of Justice suspended the registration of the party pending the elimination of the comments made.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On August 24, 2013, the 2nd party congress was held, at which the necessary amendments to the documents were adopted in order to re-submit documents to the Ministry of Justice for registration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] Earlier in the party program there was a demand to disband the Federal Security Service, which, according to the employees of the Ministry of Justice, contradicts the Constitution of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On October 22, 2013, the Ministry of Justice of the Russian Federation again refused to register the 5th of December Party as a political party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] At the beginning of 2014, the party continues to be on the list of political parties that were denied state registration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] In the 2013 Moscow mayoral election, the party organized support for the candidate from the RPR-PARNAS party, Alexei Navalny.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] In November 2013, the party issued a statement of support for Euromaidan in Ukraine.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On April 6, 2014, a new constituent congress of the "5th of December Party" was held in Moscow.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On October 27, 2014, the Ministry of Justice again refused to register the party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] On December 5, 2015, the IV Party Congress was held in Moscow on December 5.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] Congress participants discussed the work of the party in 2014-15, adopted a party development strategy for 2016-17, a new version of the party program and elected a new composition of the Federal Coordination Council of the party, consisting of 21 people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] A political statement was adopted at the end of the congress.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] The 5th of December Party has added to the list of unconditionally real political organizations, which the Ministry of Justice does not register as parties precisely because they are real political organizations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] This list, at least, should include the People's Alliance and the National Democratic Party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] They all have an asset, supporters, voters.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] All of them can successfully participate in elections. ...
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] In the elections of the mayor of Moscow, the 5th of December Party supported me and completely autonomously organized campaigning events at a level superior to the "systemic parties".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/5th-of-december-party] They always have people for pickets, and money can be collected, and lawyers, and organizers, and local deputies, and technologists.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In 1995, he graduated from the Bashkir State Pedagogical Institute in Ufa, and in 2001, from the Russian Presidential Academy of Public Administration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] He holds a Candidate of Sciences degree (Ph.D. equivalent) in political science, with a thesis titled "The Leader and the Leader’s Image in the Modern Political Process: Problems of Conceptualization and Mediatization".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] From 2001 to 2002, he served as head of the press service for the political party Union of Right Forces.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] Between 2002 and 2008, he was Deputy Plenipotentiary Envoy of the Republic of Bashkortostan to the President of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] From 2008 to 2010, he worked in the Department for Preparing Public Addresses of the Russian Government, drafting speeches for then-Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In 2010, Gallyamov returned to Bashkortostan, where until 2014 he served as Deputy Head of the Administration of the President of Bashkortostan, Rustem Khamitov.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In July 2017, he joined the Public Chamber of Krasnogorsk, Moscow Oblast.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] As a campaign manager, he participated in regional election campaigns and was a member of the Academic-Expert Council of Russia's Central Election Commission from 2018 to 2019.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In 2020, he joined the expert council of the New People political party.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] Gallyamov’s political commentary has been published in *Vedomosti*, *Forbes*, and *Republic*.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] Currently, he works as a political commentator, frequently appearing on Russian-language online media platforms and providing commentary for various international outlets.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In early 2022, Gallyamov relocated to Israel.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] On 30 September 2022, he published a report titled "The 'Successor' Project: Prospects, Conditions, and Candidates", examining the issue of power transition in Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] On February 10, 2023, the Russian justice ministry added Gallyamov to its "foreign agents" list.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] In March 2023, the Russian internal ministry placed him on a wanted list.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] Around the same time, it was reported that the Investigative Committee of Russia had opened a criminal case against him under the article on "discrediting the Russian Armed Forces".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] Media sources suggested this was linked to his April 2022 interview with the YouTube channel *Groschi* (a project of the Ukrainian TV network *1+1*), in which he discussed the Bucha massacre and the Kramatorsk railway station attack.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abbas-gallyamov] On 29 July 2024, Gallyamov was convicted in absentia and sentenced to eight years in prison.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Among other factors, the Baltic German nobility was more willing to abolish serfdom than Russian nobility and thus Baltic governorates became the testing ground for entire Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The book was promptly translated into French, Danish and Russian.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the War of 1812 and the French invasion of Kurzeme, Emperor Alexander I established a commission to improve the legal status of the peasants in Kurzeme.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In 1814, Garlieb Merkel submitted an economic study on the benefits of employing free peasants as opposed to the work of commoners to the tender announced by the Free Economic Society, which justified the abolition of serfdom in the Baltic provinces.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In the Livonian Confederation, farmers living in the castle districts retained personal freedom and self-government, but were forced to perform military and civilian duties and pay taxes.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the devastation caused by the Livonian War, the political influence and power of the manor owners increased over the peasants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the Duchy of Livonia and Duchy of Courland and Semigallia came under the rule of the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, most peasants lost their personal freedom and became the "movable" property of the nobles.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] However, personal freedom was maintained by free peasants (Vidzeme leimans and Curonian Kings), as well as city residents.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Curonian Kings was the inhabitants of seven villages of Kurzeme (Ķoniņi, Pliķi, Kalēju, Ziemeļu, Viesalga, Sausgaļi and Dragūnai), who had received special county books from masters of the Livonian Order.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In legal terms, the royals were no different from the nobles, they did not pay regular dues and did not comply with the clauses, and they were the complete determinants of the land they cultivated themselves or with the help of paid labor.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Like the nobles, the Curonian Kings had the rights of fishing, hunting, own and use mills, as well as their own coats of arms.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Since Livonian nobility provided much needed resources to support Sweden's wars it had sufficient leverage to maintain laws and social order as they see fit.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Once Livonia, Estonia and Duchy of Courland and Semigallia became part of Russian Empire local voices for abolition of serfdom emerged.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Among the first were pastor Johann Georg Eisen von Schwarzenberg and Garlieb Merkel.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Russian Empress Catherine the Great had annulled an act by Peter III that essentially freed the serfs belonging to the Orthodox Church.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] She also tried to take away serfs right to petition her.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Far away from the capital, serfs were confused as to the circumstances of her accession to the throne.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Pugachev's Rebellion of 1774 pushed Empress away from the idea of serf liberation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] During Catherine's reign (1762–1796), despite her enlightened ideals, the serfs were generally unhappy and discontented.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In October 1802, widespread Kauguri riots took place in the vicinity of Valmiera, which were suppressed only by troops.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After investigating the causes of the peasant uprising, new peasants' laws were issued in 1804, which determined that the peasants were attributed to the manor's parish and not to the landowner.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law determined the status of farmers, and the court system was reformed (parish court, land court, criminal court).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In addition, in 1809, "Additional Points to the Farmers' Law" were issued.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] In 1805, this law also came into force for the peasants of the Governorate of Estonia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Livonian Peasants Act of 1804 in effect replaced serfdom with villeinage.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Similar law was enacted with Estonian Peasants Act of 1804.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Analogous Peasantry Laws were approved by Landtags (Diet of knighthood) of the governorate of Estonia in 1816, governorate of Courland in 1817 and the governorate of Livonia in 1819 and then all has been confirmed by emperor Alexander I of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] On 23 May 1816 the Livonian Peasant Law was adopted and came into force in 1819, abolishing serfdom; the peasantry could also acquire real estate; financial leasing was introduced as a burden.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Peasant communities were to create municipalities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After a long debate, in April 1817, the Landtag of Kurzeme adopted a decision on the release of the peasants, which was approved on 25 August 1817 and announced at a solemn ceremony in the presence of Emperor Alexander I on 30 August 1818 in Jelgava.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Kurzeme Farmers' Release Law formally gave personal freedom and freedom of movement to 300,000 people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] On 26 March 1819, a similar law was approved by Vidzeme Landtag, it was promulgated on 6 January 1820 in Riga and Sāmsala.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] However, the abolition of marital status took place gradually, the so-called temporary status was established.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] With the release of the farmers, a change in the lowest administrative structure was also envisaged.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the release, for 3 years the farmers were not allowed to leave the boundaries of their parish district, but for the next 3 - the boundaries of the district of the mayor (in Kurzeme) or the boundaries of the district of the lord (Vidzeme).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] Only in 1832 did Jurģi farmers gained the right to change their place of residence within the boundaries of their province, but in Kurzeme until 1848, farmers were not allowed to settle in cities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] After the release of the peasants in 1820, Merkel published an essay dedicated to Alexander I, "Free Latvians and Estonians".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] For this, as well as for other works dedicated to the release of peasants, the monarch granted the author a lifetime pension of 300 silver rubles.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The Livonian Peasants' Law of 1849 came into force 1850. from the autumn of 1849, after publication in Estonian and Latvian.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law confirmed that the entire land was the property of the manor, but determined how it was to be used.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] That part of the land which had hitherto been at the disposal of the peasants was declared farmland, the use of which was in accordance with the free contract.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] It could be rented out as viable farms, preferably for money or sold to the peasants for real.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The law also regulated compulsory schooling.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The maintenance of the schools remained the responsibility of the municipalities, with Lutherans having to bear their own and Orthodox their own schools.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] A new link for the management of Lutheran peasant schools was the parish school government, which included a landowner, pastor, a parish school teacher and one municipality judges.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-livonia] The management of the Orthodox schools remained the responsibility of the Orthodox Church and the Synod.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Serfdom was finally abolished in Polish and Lithuanian territories during the 19th century as part of broader European reforms ending feudal obligations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In the Austrian partition, serfdom was abolished in 1848, following the revolutionary movements sweeping through Europe.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In the Prussian partition, reforms under the Stein-Hardenberg reforms ended serfdom in 1807.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In the Russian partition, the Emancipation Edict of 1861 abolished serfdom in the Russian Empire, with reforms extending to Congress Poland in 1864 following the January Uprising.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] After the First Partition of Poland of 1772, Polish peasants who found themselves in the Austrian borders noticed some changes, particularly after the Serfdom Patent of 1781.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] But still peasants could not buy the lands on their own.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Frederick the Great having gained a significant amount of land in the first partition of Poland, proceeded to introduce reforms in them which also included abolition of serfdom.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] The Polish peasants who found themselves in the Prussian borders noticed some small improvements, as the peasants couldn't be removed from land without a court order; they had the right to buy themselves out of serfdom, and send children to education aimed at attaining positions outside agriculture.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] German colonists were however given preferential treatment compared to Polish peasants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Either way, the Prussian reforms were not going as far as the Austrian ones.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] On the other hand, they were later discriminated because of their nationality (e.g.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Drzymała's wagon and the German Kulturkampf measures).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] The Polish peasants who found themselves in the Russian borders were subject to an even harsher serfdom demands than they had in Poland.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] They also had to serve in the Imperial Russian Army.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Serfdom was abolished in the Duchy of Warsaw on 22 July 1807, and in Prussia later that year on 11 November 1807.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] The reforms of the Congress Kingdom of Poland did not change the peasant situation significantly.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] The years 1830-1850 saw a raising conflict between the serfs, anti-serfdom activists and pro-serfdom governments, with increasing unrest and peasant rebellions particularly in Prussia and Austria.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In Prussia, numerous smaller reforms improved the situations of peasants over the 19th century.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In Austria, the reforms were spurred by the Kraków Uprising of 1846 and the Spring of Nations in 1848, resulting in the abolishment of serfdom in 1848.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In 1846, in Congress Poland peasants gained protection from being removed from their land, and several other beneficial changes were also implemented.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] At the same time, unrest in the villages continued, affecting about 20% of those still under serfdom.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] Following the Emancipation reform of 1861 of Western Krai and the January Uprising of 1863-1864, an emancipation reform was introduced that went beyond that of the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/abolition-of-serfdom-in-poland] In particular, peasants were allowed to regain some territories that they were removed from in the past.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] However, many of these reforms were met with intense backlash and cut back or reversed entirely, and Alexander eventually shifted towards a considerably more conservative political stance following an assassination attempt against him in 1866.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The foreign policy of Alexander was relatively pacifist, especially in comparison to his father's, although he did continue the Russian Empire's expansionist campaigns into the Far East, the Caucasus, and Central Asia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] As a consequence of the Great Game and the Crimean War, Alexander was particularly opposed to and wary of the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was also notably supportive of the United States; Alexander backed the Union during the American Civil War and even sent Russian warships to New York Harbor and San Francisco Bay to deter attacks by the Confederate Navy.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1867, he sold Alaska to the United States, owing partly to his concern that it would be nearly impossible to prevent the Russian Empire's North American colonies, which bordered British Columbia and the North-Western Territory, from falling into British hands in the event of another war.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Seeking peace and stability in the European continent, he moved away from bellicose France upon the fall of Napoleon III in 1870 and subsequently joined Germany and Austria-Hungary in the League of the Three Emperors in 1873.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Alexander's leadership, the Russian Empire engaged in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878, resulting in the independence of Bulgaria, Montenegro, Romania, and Serbia from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] His expansionism on the Far Eastern front led to the Amur Annexation, and he also approved Russian military plans on the Caucasian front that culminated in the Circassian genocide.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] While he was disappointed by the results of the Congress of Berlin in 1878, he abided by that agreement.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Among his greatest domestic challenges was a Polish uprising in January 1863, to which he responded by stripping Poland's separate constitution and directly incorporating the kingdom into the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the period preceding his assassination in 1881, Alexander had been proposing additional parliamentary reforms to counter the rise of nascent revolutionary and anarchistic movements in the region.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Born in Moscow, Alexander Nikolayevich was the eldest son of Nicholas I of Russia and Charlotte of Prussia (eldest daughter of Frederick William III of Prussia and of Louise of Mecklenburg-Strelitz).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] His early life gave little indication of his ultimate potential; until the time of his accession in 1855, aged 37, few imagined that posterity would know him for implementing the most challenging reforms undertaken in Russia since the reign of Peter the Great.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] His uncle Emperor Alexander I died childless.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Grand Duke Konstantin, the next-younger brother of Alexander I, had previously renounced his rights to the throne of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Thus, Alexander's father, who was the third son of Paul I, became the new Emperor; he took the name Nicholas I.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] At that time, Alexander became Tsesarevich as his father's heir to the throne.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the period of his life as heir apparent (1825 to 1855), the intellectual atmosphere of Saint Petersburg did not favour any kind of change: freedom of thought and all forms of private initiative were suppressed vigorously by the order of his father.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Personal and official censorship was rife; criticism of the authorities was regarded as a serious offence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The education of the tsesarevich as future emperor took place under the supervision of the liberal romantic poet and gifted translator Vasily Zhukovsky, grasping a smattering of a great many subjects and becoming familiar with the chief modern European languages.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Unusually for the time, the young Alexander was taken on a six-month tour of Russia (1837), visiting 20 provinces in the country.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He also visited many prominent Western European countries in 1838 and 1839.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] As Tsesarevich, Alexander became the first Romanov heir to visit Siberia (1837).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] While touring Russia, he also befriended the then-exiled poet Alexander Herzen and pardoned him.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] It was through Herzen's influence that he later abolished serfdom in Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1839, when his parents sent him on a tour of Europe, he met twenty-year-old Queen Victoria and they became acquainted.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Simon Sebag Montefiore speculates that a small romance emerged.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Such a marriage, however, would not work, as Alexander was not a minor prince of Europe and was in line to inherit a throne himself.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1847, Alexander donated money to Ireland during the Great Famine.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He has been described as looking like a German, somewhat of a pacifist, a heavy smoker and card player.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The death of his father gave Alexander a diplomatic headache, for his father was engaged in open warfare in the southwest of his empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 15 January 1856, the new tsar took Russia out of the Crimean War on the very unfavourable terms of the Treaty of Paris (1856), which included the loss of the Black Sea Fleet, and the provision that the Black Sea was to be a demilitarized zone similar to a contemporaneous region of the Baltic Sea.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] This gave him room to breathe and pursue an ambitious plan of domestic reforms.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraged by public opinion, Alexander began a period of radical reforms, including an attempt not to depend on landed aristocracy controlling the poor, an effort to develop Russia's natural resources, and to reform all branches of the administration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Boris Chicherin (1828–1904) was a political philosopher who believed that Russia needed a strong, authoritative government by Alexander to make the reforms possible.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II succeeded to the throne upon the death of his father in 1855.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] As Tsesarevich, he had been an enthusiastic supporter of his father's reactionary policies.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] That is, he always obeyed the autocratic ruler.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] But now he was the autocratic ruler himself, and fully intended to rule according to what he thought best.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He rejected any moves to set up a parliamentary system that would curb his powers.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He inherited a large mess that had been wrought by his father's fear of progress during his reign.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Many of the other royal families of Europe had also disliked Nicholas I, which extended to distrust of the Romanov dynasty itself.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Even so, there was no one more prepared to bring the country around than Alexander II.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The first year of his reign was devoted to the prosecution of the Crimean War and, after the fall of Sevastopol, to negotiations for peace led by his trusted counsellor, Prince Alexander Gorchakov.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The country had been exhausted and humiliated by the war.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Bribe-taking, theft and corruption were rampant.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emancipation Reform of 1861 abolished serfdom on private estates throughout the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] By this edict more than 23 million people received their liberty.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Serfs gained the full rights of free citizens, including rights to marry without having to gain consent, to own property, and to own a business.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The measure was the first and most important of the liberal reforms made by Alexander II.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Polish landed proprietors of the Lithuanian provinces presented a petition hoping that their relations with the serfs might be regulated in a way more satisfactory for the proprietors.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II authorized the formation of committees "for ameliorating the condition of the peasants", and laid down the principles on which the amelioration was to be effected.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The hint was taken: in all provinces where serfdom existed, emancipation committees were formed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Emancipation was not a simple goal capable of being achieved instantaneously by imperial decree.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] It contained complicated problems, deeply affecting the economic, social, and political future of the nation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander had to choose between the different measures recommended to him and decide, if the serfs would become agricultural laborers dependent economically and administratively on the landlords, or if the serfs would be transformed into a class of independent communal proprietors.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The emperor gave his support to the latter project, and the Russian peasantry became one of the last groups of peasants in Europe to shake off serfdom.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The architects of the emancipation manifesto were Alexander's brother Konstantin, Yakov Rostovtsev, and Nikolay Milyutin.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 3 March 1861, six years after his accession, the emancipation law was signed and published.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A host of new reforms followed in diverse areas.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The tsar appointed Dmitry Milyutin to carry out significant reforms in the Russian armed forces.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Further important changes were made concerning industry and commerce, and the new freedom thus afforded produced a large number of limited liability companies.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Plans were formed for building a great network of railways, partly to develop the natural resources of the country, and partly to increase its power for defense and attack.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Military reforms included universal conscription, introduced for all social classes on 1 January 1874.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Prior to the new regulation, as of 1861, conscription was compulsorily enforced only for the peasantry.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Conscription had been 25 years for serfs who were drafted by their landowners, which was widely considered to be a life sentence.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Other military reforms included extending the reserve forces and the military district system, which split the Russian states into 15 military districts, a system still in use over a hundred years later.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The building of strategic railways and an emphasis on the military education of the officer corps comprised further reforms.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Corporal punishment in the military and branding of soldiers as punishment were banned.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The bulk of important military reforms were enacted as a result of the poor showing in the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A new judicial administration (1864), based on the French model, introduced security of tenure.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A new penal code and a greatly simplified system of civil and criminal procedure also came into operation.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Reorganisation of the judiciary occurred to include trial in open court, with judges appointed for life, a jury system, and the creation of justices of the peace to deal with minor offences at local level.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Legal historian Sir Henry Maine credited Alexander II with the first great attempt since the time of Grotius to codify and humanise the usages of war.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Alexander's rules Jews could not own land, and were restricted in travel.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] However special taxes on Jews were eliminated and those who graduated from secondary school were permitted to live outside the Pale of Settlement, and became eligible for state employment.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Large numbers of educated Jews moved as soon as possible to Moscow, Saint Petersburg, and other major cities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Alaska colony was losing money, and would be impossible to defend in wartime against Britain, so in 1867 Russia sold Alaska to the United States for $7.2 million (equivalent to $166 million in 2025).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russian administrators, soldiers, settlers, and some of the priests returned home.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Others stayed to minister to their native parishioners, who remain members of the Russian Orthodox Church into the 21st century.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander maintained a generally liberal course.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Radicals complained he did not go far enough, and he became a target for numerous assassination plots.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He survived attempts that took place in 1866, 1879, and 1880.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] 1 March] 1881, assassins organized by the Narodnaya Volya (People's Will) party killed him with a bomb.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emperor had earlier in the day signed the Loris-Melikov constitution, which would have created two legislative commissions made up of indirectly elected representatives, had it not been repealed by his reactionary successor Alexander III.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] An attempted assassination in 1866 started a more conservative period that lasted until his death.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Tsar made a series of new appointments, replacing liberal ministers with conservatives.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Under Minister of Education Dmitry Tolstoy, liberal university courses and subjects that encouraged critical thinking were replaced by a more traditional curriculum, and from 1871 onwards only students from gymnasiums could progress to university.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1879, governors-general were established with powers to prosecute in military courts and exile political offenders.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The government also held show trials with the intention of deterring others from revolutionary activity, but after cases such as the Trial of the 193 where sympathetic juries acquitted many of the defendants, this was abandoned.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] After Alexander II became Emperor of Russia and King of Poland in 1855, he substantially relaxed the strict and repressive regime that had been imposed on Congress Poland after the November Uprising of 1830–1831.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The territories of the former Poland-Lithuania were excluded from liberal policies introduced by Alexander.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The result was the January Uprising of 1863–1864 that was suppressed after eighteen months of fighting.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Hundreds of Poles were executed, and thousands were deported to Siberia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The price of suppression was Russian support for the unification of Germany.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The martial law in Lithuania, introduced in 1863, lasted for the next 40 years.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Native languages, Ukrainian, and Belarusian, were completely banned from printed texts, the Ems Ukase being an example.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The authorities banned use of the Latin script for writing Lithuanian.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Polish language was banned in both oral and written form from all provinces except Congress Poland, where it was allowed in private conversations only.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Nikolay Milyutin was installed as governor and he decided that the best response to the January Uprising was to make reforms regarding the peasants.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He devised a program which involved the emancipation of the peasantry at the expense of the nationalist *szlachta* landowners and the expulsion of Roman Catholic priests from schools.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Emancipation of the Polish peasantry from their serf-like status took place in 1864, on more generous terms than the emancipation of Russian peasants in 1861.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1863, Alexander II re-convened the Diet of Finland and initiated several reforms increasing Finland's autonomy within the Russian Empire, including establishment of its own currency, the Finnish markka.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Liberation of business led to increased foreign investment and industrial development.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Finland also got its first railways, separately established under Finnish administration.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Finally, the elevation of Finnish from a language of the common people to a national language equal to Swedish opened opportunities for a larger proportion of Finnish society.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II is still regarded as "The Good Tsar" in Finland.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] These reforms could be seen as results of a genuine belief that reforms were easier to test in an underpopulated, homogeneous country than in the whole of Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] They may also be seen as a reward for the loyalty of its relatively western-oriented population during the Crimean War and during the Polish uprising.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraging Finnish nationalism and language can also be seen as an attempt to dilute ties with Sweden.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the Crimean War Austria maintained a policy of hostile neutrality towards Russia, and, while not going to war, was supportive of the Anglo-French coalition.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), Russia supported the Union, largely due to the view that the U.S. served as a counterbalance to their geopolitical rival, Great Britain.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1863, the Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Treaty of Paris of 1856 stood until 1871, when Prussia defeated France in the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] During his reign, Napoleon III, eager for the support of the United Kingdom, had opposed Russia over the Eastern Question.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] France abandoned its opposition to Russia after the establishment of the French Third Republic.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Encouraged by the new attitude of French diplomacy and supported by the German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck, Russia renounced the Black Sea clauses of the Paris treaty agreed to in 1856.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] As the United Kingdom with Austria could not enforce the clauses, Russia once again established a fleet in the Black Sea.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] France, after the Franco-Prussian War and the loss of Alsace–Lorraine, was fervently hostile to Germany and maintained friendly relations with Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878) the states of Romania, Serbia, and Montenegro gained international recognition of their independence while Bulgaria and Eastern Rumelia achieved their autonomy from direct Ottoman rule.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Russia took over Southern Bessarabia, lost in 1856.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russo-Circassian War (1763–1864) concluded as a Russian victory during Alexander II's rule.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Just before the conclusion of the war the Russian Army, under the emperor's order, implemented the mass-killings and extermination of Circassian "mountaineers" in the Circassian genocide, which would be often referred to as "cleansing" and "genocide" in several historic dialogues.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1857, Dmitry Milyutin first published the idea of mass expulsions of Circassian natives.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Milyutin argued that the goal was not to simply move them so that their land could be settled by productive farmers, but rather that "eliminating the Circassians was to be an end in itself – to cleanse the land of hostile elements".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A large portion of indigenous Muslim peoples of the region were ethnically cleansed from their homeland at the end of the Russo-Circassian War by Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A large deportation operation was launched against the remaining population before the end of the war in 1864 and it was mostly completed by 1867.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Only a small percentage accepted surrender and resettlement within the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The remaining Circassian populations who refused to surrender were thus variously dispersed, resettled, or killed *en masse*.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1876, the Bulgarian population in the Balkans rebelled against Ottoman rule.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Ottoman authorities suppressed the April Uprising, causing a general outcry throughout Europe.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Some of the most prominent intellectuals and politicians on the Continent, most notably Victor Hugo and William Gladstone, sought to raise awareness about the atrocities that the Turks imposed on the Bulgarian population.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] To solve this new crisis in the "Eastern question" a Constantinople Conference was convened by the Great Powers in Constantinople at the end of the year.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The participants in the Conference failed to reach a final agreement.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] After the failure of the Constantinople Conference, at the beginning of 1877, Emperor Alexander II started diplomatic preparations with the other Great Powers to secure their neutrality in case of a war between Russia and the Ottomans.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II considered such agreements paramount in avoiding the possibility of causing his country a disaster similar to the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Russian Emperor succeeded in his diplomatic endeavors.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Having secured agreement as to non-involvement by the other Great Powers, on 17 April 1877 Russia declared war upon the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The treaty and the subsequent Congress of Berlin (June–July 1878) secured the emergence of an independent Bulgarian state for the first time since 1396, and Bulgarian parliamentarians elected the tsar's nephew, Prince Alexander of Battenberg, as the Bulgarians' first ruler.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] For his social reforms in Russia and his role in the liberation of Bulgaria, Alexander II became known in Bulgaria as the "Tsar-Liberator of Russians and Bulgarians".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A monument to Alexander II was erected in 1907 in Sofia in the "National Assembly" square, opposite to the Parliament building.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The monument underwent a complete reconstruction in 2012, funded by the Sofia Municipality and some Russian foundations.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The inscription on the monument reads in Old-Bulgarian style: "To the Tsar-Liberator from grateful Bulgaria".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] There is a museum dedicated to Alexander in the Bulgarian city of Pleven.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1866, there was an attempt on the emperor's life in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] To commemorate his narrow escape from death (which he himself referred to only as "the event of 4 April 1866"), a number of churches and chapels were built in many Russian cities.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Viktor Hartmann, a Russian architect, even sketched a design of a monumental gate (which was never built) to commemorate the event.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Modest Mussorgsky later wrote his piano suite *Pictures at an Exhibition*, the last movement of which, "The Great Gate of Kiev", is based on Hartmann's sketches.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] During the 1867 World's Fair in Paris, Polish immigrant Antoni Berezowski attacked the carriage containing Alexander, his two sons and Napoleon III.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] His self-modified double-barreled pistol misfired and struck the horse of an escorting cavalryman.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] On the morning of 20 April 1879, Alexander was briskly walking towards the Square of the Guards Staff and faced Alexander Soloviev, a 33-year-old former student.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Having seen a menacing revolver in his hands, the Emperor fled in a zigzag pattern.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Soloviev fired five times but missed; he was sentenced to death and hanged on 28 May.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The student acted on his own, but other revolutionaries were keen to murder Alexander.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In December 1879, the *Narodnaya Volya* (People's Will), a radical revolutionary group which hoped to ignite a social revolution, organised an explosion on the railway from Livadia to Moscow, but they missed the emperor's train.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] On the evening of 5 February 1880, Stephan Khalturin, also from *Narodnaya Volya*, set off a timed charge under the dining room of the Winter Palace, right in the resting room of the guards a story below, killing 11 people and wounding 30 others.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] After the last assassination attempt in February 1880, Count Loris-Melikov was appointed the head of the Supreme Executive Commission and given extraordinary powers to fight the revolutionaries.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Loris-Melikov's proposals called for some form of parliamentary body, and the Emperor seemed to agree; these plans were never realized.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] 1 March] 1881, Alexander was assassinated in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] As he was known to do every Sunday for many years, the emperor went to the Mikhailovsky Manège for the military roll call.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He travelled both to and from the *Manège* in a closed carriage accompanied by five Cossacks and Frank (Franciszek) Joseph Jackowski, a Polish noble, with a sixth Cossack sitting on the coachman's left.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The emperor's carriage was followed by two sleighs carrying, among others, the chief of police and the chief of the emperor's guards.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The route, as always, was via the Catherine Canal and over the Pevchesky Bridge.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The street was flanked by narrow pavements for the public.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A young member of the *Narodnaya Volya* ("People's Will") movement, Nikolai Rysakov, was carrying a small white package wrapped in a handkerchief.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The explosion, while killing one of the Cossacks and seriously wounding the driver and people on the sidewalk, had only damaged the bulletproof carriage, a gift from Napoleon III of France.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Rysakov was captured almost immediately.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Police Chief Dvorzhitzky heard Rysakov shout out to someone else in the gathering crowd.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Dvorzhitzky offered to drive the Tsar back to the Palace in his sleigh.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Tsar agreed, but he decided to first see the culprit, and to survey the damage.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He expressed solicitude for the victims.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] To the anxious inquires of his entourage, Alexander replied, "Thank God, I'm untouched".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Nevertheless, a second young member of the *Narodnaya Volya*, Ignacy Hryniewiecki, standing by the canal fence, raised both arms and threw something at the emperor's feet.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was alleged to have shouted, "It is too early to thank God".
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Later, it was learnt there was a third bomber in the crowd.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Ivan Emelyanov stood ready, clutching a briefcase containing a bomb that was to be used if the other two bombers failed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander was carried by sleigh to the Winter Palace to his study where almost the same day twenty years earlier, he had signed the Emancipation Edict freeing the serfs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander was bleeding to death, with broken legs, bleeding knees, his stomach ripped open, and his face mutilated.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Members of the Romanov family came rushing to the scene.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The dying emperor was given Communion and Last Rites.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] When the attending physician, Sergey Botkin, was asked how long it would be, he replied, "Up to fifteen minutes." At 3:30 that day, the standard of Alexander II (his personal flag) was lowered for the last time.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II's death caused a great setback for the reform movement.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] One of his last acts was the approval of Mikhail Loris-Melikov's constitutional reforms.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Instead, following his succession, Alexander III, under the advice of Konstantin Pobedonostsev, chose to abandon his father's reforms and went on to pursue a policy of reactionism and greater autocratic power.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The assassination triggered major suppression of civil liberties in Russia, and police brutality burst back in full force after experiencing some restraint under the reign of Alexander II, whose death was witnessed firsthand by his son, Alexander III, and his grandson, Nicholas II.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Vowing not to have the same fate befall them, both emperors brought back repressive state security practices and curtailed the liberal judicial reforms implemented by Alexander II.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Further, both of them assiduously used the Okhrana, a secret police service, to arrest protestors, spy on perceived dissidents, and uproot suspected rebel groups, creating further suppression of personal freedom for the Russian people.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] A series of anti-Jewish pogroms and antisemitic legislation, the May Laws, were yet another outcome of Alexander II's assassination.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1881, the Alexander Church, designed by Theodor Decker and named after Alexander II, was completed in Tampere.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Also, with construction starting in 1883, the Church of the Savior on Blood was built on the site of Alexander's assassination and dedicated in his memory.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1838–39, the young bachelor, Alexander made the Grand Tour of Europe which was standard for young men of his class at that time.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] One of the purposes of the tour was to select a suitable bride for himself.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] His father Nicholas I of Russia suggested Princess Alexandrine of Baden as a suitable choice, but he was prepared to allow Alexander to choose his own bride, as long as she was not Roman Catholic or a commoner.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander stayed for three days with the maiden Queen Victoria.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The two got along well, but there was no question of marriage between two major monarchs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In Germany, Alexander made an unplanned stop in Darmstadt.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was reluctant to spend "a possibly dull evening" with their host Louis II, Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine, but he agreed to do so because Vasily Zhukovsky insisted that his entourage was exhausted and needed a rest.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] During dinner, he met and was charmed by Princess Marie, the 14-year-old daughter of Louis II.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He was so smitten that he declared that he would rather abandon the succession than not marry her.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He wrote to his father: "I liked her terribly at first sight.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] If you permit it, dear father, I will come back to Darmstadt after England." When he left Darmstadt, she gave him a locket that contained a piece of her hair.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's parents initially did not support his decision to marry Princess Marie of Hesse.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] There were troubling rumors about her paternity.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Although she was the legal daughter of Louis II, there were rumors that Marie was the biological daughter of her mother's lover, Baron August von Senarclens de Grancy.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's parents worried that Marie could have inherited her mother's tendency to consumption.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's mother considered the Hesse family grossly inferior to the Hohenzollerns and Romanovs.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In April 1840, Alexander's engagement to Princess Marie was officially announced.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In August, the 16-year-old Marie left Darmstadt for Russia.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In December, she was received into the Orthodox Church and received the names *Maria Alexandrovna*.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] On 16 April 1841, aged 23, Tsesarevitch Alexander married Marie in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander particularly placed hope in his eldest son, Tsesarevich Nicholas.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1864, Alexander II found Nicholas a bride, Princess Dagmar of Denmark, second daughter of King Christian IX of Denmark and younger sister to Alexandra, Princess of Wales and King George I of Greece.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1865, Nicholas died of cerebrospinal meningitis.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's second son, Grand Duke Alexander became heir and married his late brother's fiancée.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The couple married in November 1866, with Dagmar converting to Orthodoxy and taking the name Maria Feodorovna.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander grew estranged from his second son, Grand Duke Alexander.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's favorite child was his daughter, Grand Duchess Marie Alexandrovna.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] He reflected that his daughter had "never caused us anything but joy.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The tsar objected to the queen's request to have his daughter come to England in order to meet her, and after the January 1874 wedding in St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Petersburg, the tsar insisted that his daughter be granted precedence over the Princess of Wales, which the queen rebuffed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Later that year, after attending the engagement ceremonies of his second surviving son, Vladimir, to Marie of Mecklenburg-Schwerin in Berlin, Alexander II, with his third son, Alexei, accompanying him, made a visit to England.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Disraeli observed of the tsar that "his mien and manners are gracious and graceful, but the expression of his countenance, which I could now very closely examine, is sad.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1866, Alexander II took a mistress, Catherine Dolgorukova, with whom he would father three surviving children.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In 1880, he moved his mistress and their children into the Winter Palace.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander's affair alienated all his children except Alexei and Marie Alexandrovna.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Courtiers spread stories that the dying Empress Marie was forced to hear the noise of Catherine's children moving about overhead, but their respective rooms were actually far.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In May 1880, Grand Duchess Marie Alexandrovna visited Russia to see her dying mother.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] She was horrified to learn that Catherine lived in the Palace and she confronted him.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Shocked by the loss of support from his daughter, he quietly retreated to Gatchina Palace for military reviews.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The quarrel, however, evidently, jolted his conscience enough to lead him to return to St.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Petersburg each morning to ask after his wife's health.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Empress Marie Alexandrovna suffered from tuberculosis.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] 6 July] 1880, Alexander II married his mistress Catherine Dolgorukova morganatically in a secret ceremony at Tsarskoye Selo.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The action scandalized both his family and the court.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] It violated Orthodox custom which required a minimum period of 40 days mourning between the death of a spouse and the remarriage of a surviving spouse, eliciting criticism in foreign courts.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander bestowed on Catherine the title of Princess Yurievskaya and legitimized their children.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II appears prominently in the opening two chapters of Jules Verne's *Michael Strogoff* (published in 1876 during Alexander's own lifetime).
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The Emperor sets the book's plot in motion and sends its eponymous protagonist on the dangerous and vital mission which would occupy the rest of the book.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Verne presents Alexander II in a highly positive light, as an enlightened yet firm monarch, dealing confidently and decisively with a rebellion.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The films *Katia* (1938) and *Magnificent Sinner* (1959) depict a highly fictionalized account of the Tsar's romance with the woman who became his second wife.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In *The Tiger in the Well*, Philip Pullman refers to the assassination – though he never names Alexander – and to the pogroms that followed.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The anti-Jewish attacks play an important role in the novel's plot.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Andrew Williams's historical thriller, To Kill A Tsar, tells the story of The People's Will revolutionaries and the assassination through the eyes of an Anglo-Russian doctor living in St Petersburg.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] In the alternate history collection *Back in the USSA* (1997) by Eugene Byrne and Kim Newman, the first known point of divergence is that Alexander lived beyond 1881 and was able to complete his reforms.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Oscar Wilde's first play, *Vera; or, The Nihilists*, written in 1879, features Russian revolutionaries who seek to assassinate a fictional tsar.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] It was originally planned to be staged in 1881 in London, but when Alexander II was actually assassinated that year, the play was canceled.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] The play was produced again in New York in 1883, but to poor reviews, and has remained virtually unknown ever since.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Alexander II's reasons to sell Alaska to the United States in 1867 are fictionized in the epilogue of the novel *Forty-Ninth* by Boris Pronsky and Craig Britton, in a form of a letter to Catherine Dolgorukova.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Prior to that, the book explores the events immediately after the first assassination attempt on the Tsar in 1866, as well as the relationship with his brother, Grand Duke Konstantin Nikolayevich.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] Mark Twain describes a short visit with Alexander II in Chapter 37 of *The Innocents Abroad*, describing him as "very tall and spare, and a determined-looking man, though a very pleasant-looking one nevertheless.
[src:alexander-ii-of-russia/alexander-ii-of-russia] It is easy to see that he is kind and affectionate.
